00:01:46.740 --> 00:01:48.800
But anyway, it's just
not a very steep road

00:01:48.800 --> 00:01:52.510
because everything was brought
up by horse and carriage

00:01:52.510 --> 00:01:56.360
So here's a photo from 1900.

00:01:56.360 --> 00:01:59.370
In 1888, when the
observatory was completed,

00:01:59.370 --> 00:02:03.310
it was the world's first remote
mountain top observatory.

00:02:03.310 --> 00:02:04.920
Prior to that
time, observatories

00:02:04.920 --> 00:02:09.600
were on university campuses that
tended to be in large cities

00:02:09.600 --> 00:02:10.930
at or near sea level.

00:02:10.930 --> 00:02:13.190
But this was a
very remote place.

00:02:13.190 --> 00:02:17.680
And it was arguably the birth
of big science in the whole US,

00:02:17.680 --> 00:02:19.600
but certainly in the Western US.

00:02:19.600 --> 00:02:22.400
And it was made possible
by a generous donation

00:02:22.400 --> 00:02:24.170
from James Lick.

00:02:24.170 --> 00:02:26.050
James Lick has a very
interesting history.

00:02:26.050 --> 00:02:27.770
I don't have time to
go into most of it.

00:02:27.770 --> 00:02:31.770
But suffice it to say that he
came to San Francisco, which

00:02:31.770 --> 00:02:36.640
was then Yerba Buena, at the
beginning of January, 1848,

00:02:36.640 --> 00:02:40.400
when it was a little shanty
town of perhaps 1,000 people.

00:02:40.400 --> 00:02:43.140
He already had
considerable wealth.

00:02:43.140 --> 00:02:45.920
And he had the good
fortune of arriving

00:02:45.920 --> 00:02:50.640
17 days before gold was
discovered at Sutter's Mill.

00:02:50.640 --> 00:02:54.330
He tried himself looking for
gold for three or four days

00:02:54.330 --> 00:02:57.090
and then realized that this
is just not the way to go.

00:02:57.090 --> 00:02:59.410
He wants to deal
with real estate,

00:02:59.410 --> 00:03:01.960
but not with the
dirt in his fingers.

00:03:01.960 --> 00:03:05.090
So what he did is
he bought up land

00:03:05.090 --> 00:03:08.750
that people were selling in
order to go and hunt for gold.

00:03:08.750 --> 00:03:12.320
And then he sold it back to them
after they started coming back.

00:03:12.320 --> 00:03:15.120
And of course, the Gold Rush
brought lots and lots of people

00:03:15.120 --> 00:03:16.290
into California.

00:03:16.290 --> 00:03:18.830
So within three
years, San Francisco

00:03:18.830 --> 00:03:21.680
was a booming city
of 20,000 or 30,000.

00:03:21.680 --> 00:03:24.250
And Lick basically owned
a good fraction of it,

00:03:24.250 --> 00:03:27.850
as well as good fractions of the
rest of California-- Catalina

00:03:27.850 --> 00:03:31.640
Island, parts of Napa
Valley, and places like that.

00:03:31.640 --> 00:03:35.690
So he made a very large amount
of money, very, very large.

00:03:35.690 --> 00:03:37.150
Near the end of
his life, he wanted

00:03:37.150 --> 00:03:40.560
to use that money to
commemorate his parents,

00:03:40.560 --> 00:03:41.660
the memory of his parents.

00:03:41.660 --> 00:03:45.570
And so he was thinking maybe
of having statues erected

00:03:45.570 --> 00:03:48.260
of his parents on Ocean
Beach facing the Pacific

00:03:48.260 --> 00:03:51.810
Ocean until it was pointed
out to him that if we are ever

00:03:51.810 --> 00:03:54.300
attacked from the west, these
would be the first structures

00:03:54.300 --> 00:03:56.890
to come down, so that's
not such a good idea.

00:03:56.890 --> 00:03:59.580
So then Lick thought,
well, how about a pyramid

00:03:59.580 --> 00:04:03.160
at the corner of Fourth and
Market Streets in San Francisco

00:04:03.160 --> 00:04:05.490
to commemorate himself
and his parents?

00:04:05.490 --> 00:04:08.280
But you know, he was told that,
look, pyramids are no big deal.

00:04:08.280 --> 00:04:10.254
There are pyramids in
Egypt, Mexico, Central

00:04:10.254 --> 00:04:11.420
America, all over the place.

00:04:11.420 --> 00:04:15.090
So why not do something
really useful and new?

00:04:15.090 --> 00:04:18.470
And a friend of his
was George Davidson,

00:04:18.470 --> 00:04:21.180
who was President of the
California Academy of Sciences.

00:04:21.180 --> 00:04:24.300
And he suggested that James
Lick build a telescope.

00:04:24.300 --> 00:04:30.150
So in 1875, James
Lick donated $700,000

00:04:30.150 --> 00:04:32.190
to the building of
the world's greatest,

00:04:32.190 --> 00:04:34.360
most powerful telescope.

00:04:34.360 --> 00:04:37.140
And as a fraction
of the GDP, that's

00:04:37.140 --> 00:04:42.750
equivalent to about $1.2 billion
today, the largest gift ever,

00:04:42.750 --> 00:04:44.710
certainly, in the
physical sciences.

00:04:44.710 --> 00:04:46.000
So it was amazing.

00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:48.850
And a 36-inch
refractor was built.

00:04:48.850 --> 00:04:52.090
And James Lick is
buried at its base

00:04:52.090 --> 00:04:54.170
down underneath the floor there.

00:04:54.170 --> 00:04:55.620
And there you can
see the plaque,

00:04:55.620 --> 00:04:58.920
"Here lies the body
of James Lick."

00:04:58.920 --> 00:05:00.790
Well, that was 1888.

00:05:00.790 --> 00:05:05.190
At age 127, you might think,
what good is Lick these days?

00:05:05.190 --> 00:05:06.620
But what I want
to show you today

00:05:06.620 --> 00:05:10.020
is that it is doing cutting
edge research, technology

00:05:10.020 --> 00:05:13.630
development, student
training, and public outreach.

00:05:13.630 --> 00:05:17.520
And for all these reasons, it's
really an incredible place.

00:05:17.520 --> 00:05:21.350
And we don't just have the
1888 great refractor anymore.

00:05:21.350 --> 00:05:24.220
We have other telescopes that
have been built since then,

00:05:24.220 --> 00:05:27.370
the most recent of which
is now only two years old,

00:05:27.370 --> 00:05:29.410
the Automated Planet Finder.

00:05:29.410 --> 00:05:33.160
All of these telescopes are
small by today's standards.

00:05:33.160 --> 00:05:35.530
I'm privileged to be a
user of the mighty Keck

00:05:35.530 --> 00:05:36.600
telescopes in Hawaii.

00:05:36.600 --> 00:05:37.330
I love them.

00:05:37.330 --> 00:05:39.390
They're 10 meters in diameter.

00:05:39.390 --> 00:05:43.080
I use them to study very, very
faint, distant, exploding stars

00:05:43.080 --> 00:05:44.430
and galaxies.

00:05:44.430 --> 00:05:46.370
But the time is
so precious and it

00:05:46.370 --> 00:05:48.810
is needed by so many
astronomers that you just

00:05:48.810 --> 00:05:50.610
can't do certain
types of projects

00:05:50.610 --> 00:05:52.350
that I'll be describing here.

00:05:52.350 --> 00:05:54.640
We're planning to build
a 30-meter telescope

00:05:54.640 --> 00:05:55.610
if all goes well.

00:05:55.610 --> 00:05:58.380
And there have been some
issues, as you may have

00:05:58.380 --> 00:06:00.450
heard in the news recently.

00:06:00.450 --> 00:06:02.760
But hopefully, the 30-meter
telescope will be built.

00:06:02.760 --> 00:06:04.240
And that will be fantastic, too.

00:06:04.240 --> 00:06:07.110
We'll use it to study the
faintest, most distant objects

00:06:07.110 --> 00:06:07.870
in the universe.

00:06:07.870 --> 00:06:10.320
But time will be
very, very precious--

00:06:10.320 --> 00:06:14.567
for UC astronomers, maybe
40 nights a year in total.

00:06:14.567 --> 00:06:16.150
So there are certain
types of research

00:06:16.150 --> 00:06:18.830
that you simply can't do with
the Hubble and the 30-meter

00:06:18.830 --> 00:06:19.460
and the Kecks.

00:06:19.460 --> 00:06:21.760
But you can do them
with smaller telescopes,

00:06:21.760 --> 00:06:25.170
like at Lick, to which
you have repeated access.

00:06:25.170 --> 00:06:27.830
So that's what I want to
describe to you today.

00:06:27.830 --> 00:06:29.100
I'll start with supernovae.

00:06:29.100 --> 00:06:32.000
I have always liked
things that blow up,

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:34.244
as long as they're
used safely and stuff.

00:06:34.244 --> 00:06:36.160
You know, I'm not some
terrorist or something.

00:06:36.160 --> 00:06:39.450
But our sun will not blow
up at the end of its life.

00:06:39.450 --> 00:06:42.480
It will die a
relatively slow death.

00:06:42.480 --> 00:06:45.670
It'll become brighter than
it is now, But in a slow way.

00:06:45.670 --> 00:06:48.200
But some stars become
much, much brighter very,

00:06:48.200 --> 00:06:50.950
very quickly because
they literally explode.

00:06:50.950 --> 00:06:54.020
This is a titanic,
colossal explosion

00:06:54.020 --> 00:06:57.110
that can make the star
up to several billion

00:06:57.110 --> 00:07:01.380
times the brightness of
our sun, or the luminosity,

00:07:01.380 --> 00:07:02.210
the true power.

00:07:02.210 --> 00:07:05.830
So here is one star in this
galaxy of 100 billion stars.

00:07:05.830 --> 00:07:09.450
And at its peak, it's about as
bright as the central billion

00:07:09.450 --> 00:07:11.120
stars in this galaxy.

00:07:11.120 --> 00:07:13.280
So if our sun were to do
this-- and don't worry,

00:07:13.280 --> 00:07:16.440
it won't-- then sun block of
50 just wouldn't cut it, folks.

00:07:16.440 --> 00:07:18.910
You'd need sun block,
or supernova block,

00:07:18.910 --> 00:07:20.680
of a few billion to
protect yourself.

00:07:20.680 --> 00:07:25.050
But don't worry, be happy-- our
sun is not going to do this.

00:07:25.050 --> 00:07:28.470
When stars do do this, they're
not only exciting to watch,

00:07:28.470 --> 00:07:31.080
but they are of fundamental
importance to us,

00:07:31.080 --> 00:07:34.540
because they generate
and spew out into space

00:07:34.540 --> 00:07:37.820
the heavy elements that are so
necessary for life on Earth.

00:07:37.820 --> 00:07:40.955
So during the normal nuclear
reactions in a star, carbon

00:07:40.955 --> 00:07:43.490
and oxygen are built up
eventually-- right now

00:07:43.490 --> 00:07:45.820
our sun is forming
helium-- but those elements

00:07:45.820 --> 00:07:47.240
have no way to get out.

00:07:47.240 --> 00:07:50.580
The supernova releases them
and, during the explosion,

00:07:50.580 --> 00:07:53.020
creates additional
heavy elements.

00:07:53.020 --> 00:07:56.220
And we can look at supernova
remnants, like this one,

00:07:56.220 --> 00:08:00.150
and see that the gases are
enriched in heavy elements that

00:08:00.150 --> 00:08:03.470
simply weren't there in
any significant abundance

00:08:03.470 --> 00:08:05.670
at the time the star was born.

00:08:05.670 --> 00:08:08.780
The supernova remnants
spread out like this

00:08:08.780 --> 00:08:10.750
and then meet up with
other clouds of gas,

00:08:10.750 --> 00:08:13.800
eventually forming giant,
gravitationally-bound clouds,

00:08:13.800 --> 00:08:17.630
like the Orion Nebula, in
the center of which you

00:08:17.630 --> 00:08:20.520
can see lots of newly-formed,
or in some cases

00:08:20.520 --> 00:08:23.050
still-forming, stars.

00:08:23.050 --> 00:08:26.540
And because this gas has gone
through many, many generations

00:08:26.540 --> 00:08:29.780
of stellar birth and death
and chemical enrichment,

00:08:29.780 --> 00:08:31.610
these gases are
now significantly

00:08:31.610 --> 00:08:33.039
enriched in heavy elements.

00:08:33.039 --> 00:08:36.400
And so you can get
gas and dust disks

00:08:36.400 --> 00:08:39.780
around newly-formed stars,
which then coagulate

00:08:39.780 --> 00:08:44.770
into planets, some of which will
be rocky, Earth-like planets.

00:08:44.770 --> 00:08:46.590
And this is how our
own solar system

00:08:46.590 --> 00:08:50.190
was born 4 and 1/2 billion
years ago from gases

00:08:50.190 --> 00:08:53.270
that had gone through many,
many generations of enrichment

00:08:53.270 --> 00:08:54.480
of this sort.

00:08:54.480 --> 00:08:57.710
And somehow, somewhere-- I'll
leave this to the biologists--

00:08:57.710 --> 00:08:59.930
lifeforms-- and it evolves.

00:08:59.930 --> 00:09:01.720
I'm skipping a few steps here.

00:09:01.720 --> 00:09:03.260
And it ends up-- oops.

00:09:03.260 --> 00:09:05.240
One of the pictures
somehow got hidden.

00:09:05.240 --> 00:09:06.860
But there's part of my DNA.

00:09:06.860 --> 00:09:11.730
It ends up with people who are
sentient beings that can sit

00:09:11.730 --> 00:09:13.330
and look out into the cosmos.

00:09:13.330 --> 00:09:17.770
And my kids just attended the
Maker's Faire a short time ago

00:09:17.770 --> 00:09:19.900
and were particularly
thrilled by the Google booth,

00:09:19.900 --> 00:09:21.510
where they made
rockets and stuff.

00:09:21.510 --> 00:09:24.660
So they're going to sign up
for a Maker's Camp this summer.

00:09:24.660 --> 00:09:26.990
So anyway, we are
made of star stuff.

00:09:26.990 --> 00:09:28.740
So we would like to
understand the process

00:09:28.740 --> 00:09:30.190
by which this occurs.

00:09:30.190 --> 00:09:32.060
So we'd like to find
nearby supernovae,

00:09:32.060 --> 00:09:33.440
but they're pretty rare.

00:09:33.440 --> 00:09:35.580
So if you look at
some galaxies, you're

00:09:35.580 --> 00:09:38.000
unlikely to find supernovae,
because they only go off

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:39.560
once every 30 or 40 years.

00:09:39.560 --> 00:09:42.320
And that would be pretty boring
looking through a telescope

00:09:42.320 --> 00:09:44.640
in search of supernovae by eye.

00:09:44.640 --> 00:09:46.230
Fortunately, with
modern technology,

00:09:46.230 --> 00:09:47.550
we have a better technique.

00:09:47.550 --> 00:09:50.700
You attach CCD cameras to the
eyepiece end of a telescope,

00:09:50.700 --> 00:09:52.660
take photographs of
thousands of galaxies,

00:09:52.660 --> 00:09:53.890
and simply look for arrows.

00:09:53.890 --> 00:09:56.416
And where you see arrows,
you see exploding stars.

00:09:56.416 --> 00:09:58.790
You see it happened once,
twice, three times, four times,

00:09:58.790 --> 00:09:59.410
five times.

00:09:59.410 --> 00:10:01.330
By rigorous
mathematical induction,

00:10:01.330 --> 00:10:04.630
I conclude that this
process works every time.

00:10:04.630 --> 00:10:07.030
Well, it doesn't.

00:10:07.030 --> 00:10:09.630
You have to program
telescopes and computers

00:10:09.630 --> 00:10:13.370
to do this and software that
will look for the new objects.

00:10:13.370 --> 00:10:15.080
And so what we have
at Lick Observatory

00:10:15.080 --> 00:10:16.980
is a telescope
that's by no means

00:10:16.980 --> 00:10:18.370
large by today's standards.

00:10:18.370 --> 00:10:20.610
It's only 3/4 of a
meter in diameter.

00:10:20.610 --> 00:10:22.400
But it's been
programmed expertly

00:10:22.400 --> 00:10:25.450
by my associate Weidong
Li to look at, literally,

00:10:25.450 --> 00:10:29.110
thousands of galaxies each week
and to compare the new pictures

00:10:29.110 --> 00:10:30.400
with the old pictures.

00:10:30.400 --> 00:10:32.740
And usually, there is nothing
new in the new picture.

00:10:32.740 --> 00:10:36.151
But occasionally, you'll notice
something new, this star here.

00:10:36.151 --> 00:10:37.400
I mean, the arrow is new, too.

00:10:37.400 --> 00:10:39.656
But that was put in with
Photoshop or something.

00:10:39.656 --> 00:10:41.030
So there is a
thing that might be

00:10:41.030 --> 00:10:43.710
a supernova candidate-- or,
it is a supernova candidate.

00:10:43.710 --> 00:10:45.210
It might be a supernova.

00:10:45.210 --> 00:10:46.620
But it could be something else.

00:10:46.620 --> 00:10:49.430
It could be an asteroid flying
through the field of view,

00:10:49.430 --> 00:10:51.240
perhaps with Earth's
name written on it.

00:10:51.240 --> 00:10:53.340
Someday, astronomers
will save humanity

00:10:53.340 --> 00:10:54.810
because they'll
find the asteroids

00:10:54.810 --> 00:10:57.640
and then applied physicists
and engineers will figure out

00:10:57.640 --> 00:10:59.010
how to deflect them.

00:10:59.010 --> 00:11:02.200
But anyway, one person's garbage
is another person's gold.

00:11:02.200 --> 00:11:03.430
I don't want the asteroids.

00:11:03.430 --> 00:11:06.240
I don't want the cosmic rays,
which are charged particles

00:11:06.240 --> 00:11:07.740
that interact with the CCD.

00:11:07.740 --> 00:11:09.230
I want the supernovae.

00:11:09.230 --> 00:11:11.690
So out of a couple of dozen
candidates each night,

00:11:11.690 --> 00:11:14.220
maybe one of them will be
a supernova, maybe none.

00:11:14.220 --> 00:11:17.640
And there, I used students who,
with their superb eye-brain

00:11:17.640 --> 00:11:19.560
combination, look
at the candidates

00:11:19.560 --> 00:11:22.570
and determine which ones are
likely to be genuine supernovae

00:11:22.570 --> 00:11:24.540
worthy of further study.

00:11:24.540 --> 00:11:26.170
And these students,
often starting

00:11:26.170 --> 00:11:28.760
in their freshman year,
even, get so excited when

00:11:28.760 --> 00:11:29.910
they find a supernova.

00:11:29.910 --> 00:11:31.480
And they write home
to Mom about it.

00:11:31.480 --> 00:11:32.920
And then they analyze the data.

00:11:32.920 --> 00:11:37.540
And they get trained in lots
of science data analysis, error

00:11:37.540 --> 00:11:39.690
propagation,
statistical techniques.

00:11:39.690 --> 00:11:43.180
Most don't go on to become
professors of astrophysics

00:11:43.180 --> 00:11:44.250
at universities.

00:11:44.250 --> 00:11:48.310
Most go on and become more
immediately useful to society

00:11:48.310 --> 00:11:50.910
as engineers, applied
physicists, medical physicists,

00:11:50.910 --> 00:11:52.760
computer scientists,
people like that.

00:11:52.760 --> 00:11:56.010
But they get that early
exposure to research

00:11:56.010 --> 00:11:59.450
through groups such as mine
at Berkeley and the UC system

00:11:59.450 --> 00:12:00.140
throughout.

00:12:00.140 --> 00:12:01.890
But my point here--
and this is the mantra

00:12:01.890 --> 00:12:04.730
throughout the whole talk-- is
that for this kind of research,

00:12:04.730 --> 00:12:07.260
just having a few nights per
year on the biggest telescopes

00:12:07.260 --> 00:12:08.790
does you no good whatsoever.

00:12:08.790 --> 00:12:11.470
You need huge amounts of
time, months or years,

00:12:11.470 --> 00:12:14.160
on small or
modest-sized telescopes.

00:12:14.160 --> 00:12:16.312
Once we or others--
I'm not saying we're

00:12:16.312 --> 00:12:17.770
the only ones who
find supernovae--

00:12:17.770 --> 00:12:20.070
but once we or others
find a supernova,

00:12:20.070 --> 00:12:22.150
we'd like to study
that supernova.

00:12:22.150 --> 00:12:24.530
We collect more light
with a bigger telescope,

00:12:24.530 --> 00:12:26.200
like the 3-meter
telescope at Lick.

00:12:26.200 --> 00:12:29.690
And then we're able to spread
the light out into a spectrum,

00:12:29.690 --> 00:12:31.790
plot the intensity
versus the wavelength.

00:12:31.790 --> 00:12:33.920
And when you do this
for enough supernovae,

00:12:33.920 --> 00:12:37.110
you find that they come in
several well-defined groups--

00:12:37.110 --> 00:12:40.820
the Type I's that don't have
hydrogen and the Type II's that

00:12:40.820 --> 00:12:41.670
do.

00:12:41.670 --> 00:12:44.540
But here, you can see calcium,
oxygen, silicon, sulfur, iron,

00:12:44.540 --> 00:12:47.140
magnesium, the elements
that were generated

00:12:47.140 --> 00:12:52.030
during the star's life and
during its explosion, elements

00:12:52.030 --> 00:12:54.670
that are necessary for
Earth and for life on Earth.

00:12:54.670 --> 00:12:57.150
So there are other
types, as well.

00:12:57.150 --> 00:12:59.340
But we study them
in some detail.

00:12:59.340 --> 00:13:02.760
And getting one
spectrum isn't enough,

00:13:02.760 --> 00:13:05.100
because you're
then just sampling

00:13:05.100 --> 00:13:08.220
the chemical elements that
are on the outside parts

00:13:08.220 --> 00:13:09.500
of the star.

00:13:09.500 --> 00:13:12.150
But as the exploding
star expands,

00:13:12.150 --> 00:13:16.050
the gases thin out and
become transparent.

00:13:16.050 --> 00:13:18.930
And you see down into
deeper and deeper layers.

00:13:18.930 --> 00:13:22.170
So by getting a series
of spectra over time--

00:13:22.170 --> 00:13:24.880
from 12 days before peak
brightness, in this case,

00:13:24.880 --> 00:13:27.330
to several months
after peak brightness--

00:13:27.330 --> 00:13:30.580
you can get, essentially, a CAT
scan of this exploding star,

00:13:30.580 --> 00:13:34.420
because you see the
different layers up

00:13:34.420 --> 00:13:37.510
to where it's transparent down
to where it becomes opaque.

00:13:37.510 --> 00:13:40.190
And that boundary moves
farther and farther in.

00:13:40.190 --> 00:13:43.400
So at early times, you see
things like calcium and silicon

00:13:43.400 --> 00:13:44.160
and stuff.

00:13:44.160 --> 00:13:46.650
And at late times, you see iron.

00:13:46.650 --> 00:13:48.400
And so, in fact, that
shows that the iron

00:13:48.400 --> 00:13:50.240
is produced in the
explosion close

00:13:50.240 --> 00:13:52.150
to the center of
the exploding star.

00:13:52.150 --> 00:13:54.990
And students are involved
in the spectroscopy

00:13:54.990 --> 00:13:58.780
as well as in the discovery
of the supernovae.

00:13:58.780 --> 00:14:02.080
They also get the light
curves of the supernovae,

00:14:02.080 --> 00:14:03.970
the brightness versus time.

00:14:03.970 --> 00:14:05.460
And again, this
tells us something

00:14:05.460 --> 00:14:08.030
about the physics of what's
going on in these two

00:14:08.030 --> 00:14:10.370
main types, the Ia's Type IIs.

00:14:10.370 --> 00:14:13.050
And we do this, again,
with just a small telescope

00:14:13.050 --> 00:14:16.230
because these are bright,
nearby exploding stars.

00:14:16.230 --> 00:14:18.470
What we need is lots
and lots of time

00:14:18.470 --> 00:14:21.190
on a small telescope,
not a little bit of time

00:14:21.190 --> 00:14:22.560
on the biggest telescopes.

00:14:22.560 --> 00:14:24.890
And students are
involved throughout,

00:14:24.890 --> 00:14:27.760
more so now than ever
before, because we now

00:14:27.760 --> 00:14:30.560
have these remote
observing stations set up

00:14:30.560 --> 00:14:34.490
at each of the UC campuses,
where students can essentially

00:14:34.490 --> 00:14:36.420
talk to the telescope
operator-- or run

00:14:36.420 --> 00:14:39.720
the telescope themselves,
in this case-- get the data,

00:14:39.720 --> 00:14:40.750
analyze the data.

00:14:40.750 --> 00:14:42.670
It's as though they're
up on the summit.

00:14:42.670 --> 00:14:44.180
But they're not
up at the summit.

00:14:44.180 --> 00:14:46.920
That's great, because students
are busy with courses.

00:14:46.920 --> 00:14:48.510
And generally, they
don't have cars.

00:14:48.510 --> 00:14:51.390
And it's a four-hour round trip
from Berkeley or Santa Cruz,

00:14:51.390 --> 00:14:54.720
not even to mention UCLA,
San Diego, Riverside, Irvine.

00:14:54.720 --> 00:14:56.500
Those are all much more distant.

00:14:56.500 --> 00:15:00.230
So students are now involved
more than ever in real research

00:15:00.230 --> 00:15:01.970
because of the remote
facilities set up

00:15:01.970 --> 00:15:03.750
at the different campuses.

00:15:03.750 --> 00:15:06.500
I then have a group lunch once
a week-- my group lunch will

00:15:06.500 --> 00:15:08.840
be tomorrow--
where I bring pizza

00:15:08.840 --> 00:15:11.660
and they justify their
existence for the previous week.

00:15:11.660 --> 00:15:13.569
They'll do anything,
undergraduates and grad

00:15:13.569 --> 00:15:15.110
students and postdocs,
for free food.

00:15:15.110 --> 00:15:17.530
And we just discuss
all of our projects.

00:15:17.530 --> 00:15:19.010
And everyone helps each other.

00:15:19.010 --> 00:15:21.790
It's a really
groupthink-type experience.

00:15:21.790 --> 00:15:22.610
It's wonderful.

00:15:22.610 --> 00:15:25.010
But again, to get
spectra and light curves,

00:15:25.010 --> 00:15:26.570
you need lots and lots of time.

00:15:26.570 --> 00:15:27.850
That's the mantra.

00:15:27.850 --> 00:15:31.110
And someone who was very
inspired by the work we

00:15:31.110 --> 00:15:34.340
did in setting up the Katzman
telescope and the success

00:15:34.340 --> 00:15:37.360
we achieved with it was,
in fact, Wayne Rosing,

00:15:37.360 --> 00:15:40.650
who left Google some years
ago and has started up

00:15:40.650 --> 00:15:44.600
this gigantic thing called the
Las Cumbres Observatory Global

00:15:44.600 --> 00:15:45.720
Telescope Network.

00:15:45.720 --> 00:15:48.290
He and his team in Santa
Barbara have set up

00:15:48.290 --> 00:15:51.065
telescopes of this sort
modeled after our telescope

00:15:51.065 --> 00:15:52.750
at Lick throughout the world.

00:15:52.750 --> 00:15:57.560
And their motto is, "The
sun never rises on LCOGT."

00:15:57.560 --> 00:15:59.720
In other words,
at some longitude,

00:15:59.720 --> 00:16:03.480
there's always a telescope
where the sun is down.

00:16:03.480 --> 00:16:05.600
So that's fantastic.

00:16:05.600 --> 00:16:09.120
I want to tell you one
application of the Type Ia

00:16:09.120 --> 00:16:09.680
supernovae.

00:16:09.680 --> 00:16:12.420
And this was the subject of
my talk back in November.

00:16:12.420 --> 00:16:13.920
So if you want to
hear more details,

00:16:13.920 --> 00:16:15.860
you can go online
and watch that talk.

00:16:15.860 --> 00:16:19.260
But the point is that the
universe is expanding.

00:16:19.260 --> 00:16:22.080
We've known that ever
since Hubble's work, which

00:16:22.080 --> 00:16:25.700
showed that the
light from galaxies

00:16:25.700 --> 00:16:28.830
is shifted toward longer
wavelengths, redder

00:16:28.830 --> 00:16:29.590
wavelengths.

00:16:29.590 --> 00:16:33.340
And the greater the distance,
the greater is this redshift.

00:16:33.340 --> 00:16:35.380
And we now know
that this is because

00:16:35.380 --> 00:16:37.300
of an expansion of space itself.

00:16:37.300 --> 00:16:40.290
Hubble himself resisted
that interpretation back

00:16:40.290 --> 00:16:43.340
in the late 1920s
and early 1930s.

00:16:43.340 --> 00:16:45.660
But we now know
that it's the case.

00:16:45.660 --> 00:16:49.440
And so you look at all these
galaxies, and you wonder, well,

00:16:49.440 --> 00:16:52.610
will they keep on expanding
away from each other forever?

00:16:52.610 --> 00:16:57.430
Or will they someday return
back into a denser structure?

00:16:57.430 --> 00:17:00.199
And if the density
is big enough--

00:17:00.199 --> 00:17:01.990
the density of the
universe, visible matter

00:17:01.990 --> 00:17:03.450
and dark matter--
then everything

00:17:03.450 --> 00:17:06.010
will pull in everything else
so much that, eventually,

00:17:06.010 --> 00:17:07.250
the expansion will stop.

00:17:07.250 --> 00:17:09.280
And then it will reverse itself.

00:17:09.280 --> 00:17:10.980
And the universe will implode.

00:17:10.980 --> 00:17:12.890
So Big Bang, Big Crunch.

00:17:12.890 --> 00:17:14.960
Or you could say, Big
Bang, "gnab, gib,"

00:17:14.960 --> 00:17:16.740
which is Big Bang backwards.

00:17:16.740 --> 00:17:18.640
And so if you were
in this universe

00:17:18.640 --> 00:17:20.970
and lying on your back
looking at the galaxies,

00:17:20.970 --> 00:17:23.266
they would look progressively
fainter and smaller.

00:17:23.266 --> 00:17:25.349
And you would say, yes, I
live in a good universe.

00:17:25.349 --> 00:17:27.480
And then you'd notice
something a bit peculiar.

00:17:27.480 --> 00:17:29.970
And right around now, you'd
start getting a little nervous.

00:17:29.970 --> 00:17:31.790
And then, you know,
goodbye, cruel world,

00:17:31.790 --> 00:17:34.340
because the universe
would collapse in on you.

00:17:34.340 --> 00:17:35.220
All right.

00:17:35.220 --> 00:17:37.040
On the other hand,
you might live

00:17:37.040 --> 00:17:39.440
in a sufficiently
low-density universe

00:17:39.440 --> 00:17:41.660
that the expansion,
though slowing down

00:17:41.660 --> 00:17:43.930
with time because of
gravity, never quite

00:17:43.930 --> 00:17:45.230
comes to a complete stop.

00:17:45.230 --> 00:17:47.230
And that's, of course,
like launching something

00:17:47.230 --> 00:17:49.850
at a speed greater than
Earth's escape speed.

00:17:49.850 --> 00:17:51.900
In that case, the
galaxies would continue

00:17:51.900 --> 00:17:54.790
to get fainter and smaller
in the sky forever,

00:17:54.790 --> 00:17:58.190
albeit at a progressively
decreasing rate, because there

00:17:58.190 --> 00:18:00.400
is some gravity
acting upon them.

00:18:00.400 --> 00:18:02.600
Well, we would like to know
which kind of a universe

00:18:02.600 --> 00:18:03.516
we live in, all right?

00:18:03.516 --> 00:18:06.240
And so here's the scale
factor, the distance

00:18:06.240 --> 00:18:09.090
between two clusters of
galaxies versus time.

00:18:09.090 --> 00:18:11.040
Here's the universe
that expands for a while

00:18:11.040 --> 00:18:13.340
and then undergoes a Big Crunch.

00:18:13.340 --> 00:18:14.870
Here's an empty universe.

00:18:14.870 --> 00:18:16.770
It expands forever
at the same rate

00:18:16.770 --> 00:18:17.964
because there is no gravity.

00:18:17.964 --> 00:18:20.130
Clearly, we're somewhere
in between because it's not

00:18:20.130 --> 00:18:21.580
an empty universe.

00:18:21.580 --> 00:18:23.560
Here's sort of a
medium-density universe.

00:18:23.560 --> 00:18:26.480
This is one that expands
forever, but just barely.

00:18:26.480 --> 00:18:29.310
And most measurements of
the density of the universe

00:18:29.310 --> 00:18:32.300
suggested back in
the early 1990s

00:18:32.300 --> 00:18:35.010
that we live in a universe
that has about 30%

00:18:35.010 --> 00:18:36.550
of the critical density.

00:18:36.550 --> 00:18:40.850
That is, it's a universe that
will expand forever easily,

00:18:40.850 --> 00:18:42.950
not just barely.

00:18:42.950 --> 00:18:47.460
But it would be interesting to
see whether this is actually

00:18:47.460 --> 00:18:51.604
supported by a measurement
of the past history

00:18:51.604 --> 00:18:52.270
of the universe.

00:18:52.270 --> 00:18:54.800
In other words,
which of these curves

00:18:54.800 --> 00:18:57.050
has the universe been following?

00:18:57.050 --> 00:19:00.140
Then we could predict what
it will do in the past.

00:19:00.140 --> 00:19:04.189
So we want to measure the
expansion history to determine

00:19:04.189 --> 00:19:05.230
the fate of the universe.

00:19:05.230 --> 00:19:07.620
It's a little bit like
measuring the speed of the apple

00:19:07.620 --> 00:19:08.850
at many, many times.

00:19:08.850 --> 00:19:10.760
Seeing how much it's
slowing down from that,

00:19:10.760 --> 00:19:13.240
you can calculate whether
it'll speed up or not.

00:19:13.240 --> 00:19:17.140
So let's look at the left part
of this diagram more closely.

00:19:17.140 --> 00:19:20.660
The definition of the redshift
is that 1 plus the redshift

00:19:20.660 --> 00:19:24.166
is simply the scale
factor of the universe--

00:19:24.166 --> 00:19:25.540
the distance
between two clusters

00:19:25.540 --> 00:19:29.350
of galaxies now-- divided
by what it was back

00:19:29.350 --> 00:19:30.590
when the light was emitted.

00:19:30.590 --> 00:19:33.220
So redshift 0--
well, 1 plus 0 is 1.

00:19:33.220 --> 00:19:35.350
Even a non-Googler
understands that.

00:19:35.350 --> 00:19:36.760
And so this ratio is 1.

00:19:36.760 --> 00:19:38.750
Redshift 1-- well, that
means that the light

00:19:38.750 --> 00:19:41.950
was emitted when the universe
was essentially half its size.

00:19:41.950 --> 00:19:46.400
So let's draw a line
now, redshift 0.

00:19:46.400 --> 00:19:47.840
And let's go to redshift 1.

00:19:47.840 --> 00:19:51.050
At that time, the universe
was half its size.

00:19:51.050 --> 00:19:53.280
You can see that, depending
on the past history

00:19:53.280 --> 00:19:56.190
of the universe,
redshift 1 corresponds

00:19:56.190 --> 00:20:00.160
to different lookback times,
and hence different distances,

00:20:00.160 --> 00:20:01.980
because light travels
through the universe

00:20:01.980 --> 00:20:03.240
at the speed of light.

00:20:03.240 --> 00:20:05.340
The lookback time, and
hence the distance,

00:20:05.340 --> 00:20:09.080
of a redshift 1 object is
smallest for a dense universe,

00:20:09.080 --> 00:20:11.450
bigger for a less
dense, medium universe,

00:20:11.450 --> 00:20:13.590
bigger still for a
low-density universe,

00:20:13.590 --> 00:20:16.320
bigger still for
an empty universe.

00:20:16.320 --> 00:20:20.020
So the functional form between
the redshift and the distance

00:20:20.020 --> 00:20:27.830
is what ends up being a measure
of what kind of a universe

00:20:27.830 --> 00:20:28.330
we live in.

00:20:28.330 --> 00:20:29.788
You want to measure
that functional

00:20:29.788 --> 00:20:33.400
form between the lookback time
or distance and the redshift.

00:20:33.400 --> 00:20:36.070
The theoretical models give
you a different functional form

00:20:36.070 --> 00:20:38.000
depending on what
universe you live in.

00:20:38.000 --> 00:20:41.350
And of course, all these
curves meet right here.

00:20:41.350 --> 00:20:45.190
Now two clusters have
whatever separation

00:20:45.190 --> 00:20:47.370
they have, and they're
expanding at whatever

00:20:47.370 --> 00:20:48.720
the current expansion rate is.

00:20:48.720 --> 00:20:49.790
That's the slope.

00:20:49.790 --> 00:20:51.800
So all these curves
have to meet now.

00:20:51.800 --> 00:20:54.810
But they diverge as
you go back in time.

00:20:54.810 --> 00:20:56.580
And that's what this
graph is showing.

00:20:56.580 --> 00:20:58.860
That's the theoretical view.

00:20:58.860 --> 00:21:00.550
Here's the observational view.

00:21:00.550 --> 00:21:04.810
If you measure redshift and
distance and plot the points--

00:21:04.810 --> 00:21:06.610
this part is what Hubble found.

00:21:06.610 --> 00:21:08.530
You go out to big
enough redshifts,

00:21:08.530 --> 00:21:11.500
you should see which
of these curves

00:21:11.500 --> 00:21:12.950
the universe has been following.

00:21:12.950 --> 00:21:15.490
And that will tell you
the cosmological model

00:21:15.490 --> 00:21:17.030
that applies to our universe.

00:21:17.030 --> 00:21:18.540
So redshifts are
easy to measure.

00:21:18.540 --> 00:21:20.514
Just get a spectrum
and see how much

00:21:20.514 --> 00:21:21.680
the lines have been shifted.

00:21:21.680 --> 00:21:22.340
Here's 0.

00:21:22.340 --> 00:21:23.906
Here, by 10%.

00:21:23.906 --> 00:21:25.670
So that galaxy is
moving away from us

00:21:25.670 --> 00:21:27.046
at 30,000 kilometers per second.

00:21:27.046 --> 00:21:27.670
So that's easy.

00:21:27.670 --> 00:21:28.760
Redshifts are easy.

00:21:28.760 --> 00:21:30.780
Distances are a bit harder.

00:21:30.780 --> 00:21:32.390
The way we do it
is the same way you

00:21:32.390 --> 00:21:34.460
judge the distance of an
oncoming car at night.

00:21:34.460 --> 00:21:36.751
You look at the relative
brightnesses of the headlights

00:21:36.751 --> 00:21:38.960
and you use the inverse
square law in your mind.

00:21:38.960 --> 00:21:42.440
Well, for galaxies that are
sufficiently distant to apply

00:21:42.440 --> 00:21:45.030
this test, you're not going
to see individual stars,

00:21:45.030 --> 00:21:47.720
because these galaxies are
billions of light years away.

00:21:47.720 --> 00:21:49.820
So you're not going to see
a sun-like star or even

00:21:49.820 --> 00:21:52.500
a fairly bright star, like
a Cepheid variable, which

00:21:52.500 --> 00:21:55.140
is what Edwin Hubble used
to get the low redshift

00:21:55.140 --> 00:21:56.720
end of the Hubble diagram.

00:21:56.720 --> 00:21:58.890
But supernovae, in
fact, are bright enough

00:21:58.890 --> 00:22:01.250
to be seen at distances of
billions of light years.

00:22:01.250 --> 00:22:02.190
That's the key.

00:22:02.190 --> 00:22:05.400
So you can measure nearby ones
in galaxies whose distance you

00:22:05.400 --> 00:22:07.290
already know through
some other technique,

00:22:07.290 --> 00:22:08.910
like measuring
Cepheid variables.

00:22:08.910 --> 00:22:11.630
And then you find one in
some pathetic little galaxy,

00:22:11.630 --> 00:22:12.130
like this.

00:22:12.130 --> 00:22:12.650
There it is.

00:22:12.650 --> 00:22:16.310
You subtract one epoch from
another, and you find it.

00:22:16.310 --> 00:22:18.310
And you can take
measurements of it

00:22:18.310 --> 00:22:21.090
and do the inverse square law
and figure out the distance,

00:22:21.090 --> 00:22:22.910
and hence the lookback time.

00:22:22.910 --> 00:22:24.170
So that's the idea.

00:22:24.170 --> 00:22:28.010
And this is best done with
the subclass called Type Ia's.

00:22:28.010 --> 00:22:31.604
These are quite standard
in how powerful they are.

00:22:31.604 --> 00:22:33.520
And that's because they
come from a weird type

00:22:33.520 --> 00:22:35.770
of a star called a white dwarf.

00:22:35.770 --> 00:22:38.260
Our own sun will turn
into a white dwarf

00:22:38.260 --> 00:22:40.360
in about 7 billion
years, at which time

00:22:40.360 --> 00:22:43.260
it will be about the
size of the Earth.

00:22:43.260 --> 00:22:44.544
And it won't explode.

00:22:44.544 --> 00:22:46.210
It'll just sort of
sit there, because it

00:22:46.210 --> 00:22:47.540
doesn't have a companion.

00:22:47.540 --> 00:22:50.760
But those that have a
sufficiently nearby companion

00:22:50.760 --> 00:22:54.980
can steal material from that
companion, grow in mass,

00:22:54.980 --> 00:22:57.590
and eventually reach an
unstable limit, at which point

00:22:57.590 --> 00:22:58.520
they explode.

00:22:58.520 --> 00:23:01.680
And that unstable limit
should be the same each time.

00:23:01.680 --> 00:23:05.280
And so they should explode in
exactly the same way each time

00:23:05.280 --> 00:23:08.070
and reach the same
peak luminosity.

00:23:08.070 --> 00:23:13.910
That's true to first order.

00:23:13.910 --> 00:23:15.520
But when you look
more carefully,

00:23:15.520 --> 00:23:19.240
such as the work that my
team did in the early 1990s,

00:23:19.240 --> 00:23:22.040
you find that there are,
in fact, differences

00:23:22.040 --> 00:23:23.930
among the Type Ia supernovae.

00:23:23.930 --> 00:23:27.080
Even though they are all
approximately the same,

00:23:27.080 --> 00:23:29.150
when you look carefully,
there are differences.

00:23:29.150 --> 00:23:31.590
And here's spectra
of three supernovae

00:23:31.590 --> 00:23:34.490
that I studied in
the early 1990s.

00:23:34.490 --> 00:23:36.950
You can see that there are
spectroscopic differences

00:23:36.950 --> 00:23:38.450
among them.

00:23:38.450 --> 00:23:40.800
There are differences
in various places.

00:23:40.800 --> 00:23:44.306
This big absorption
trough here is not that--

00:23:44.306 --> 00:23:47.060
And in fact, measurements
of their peak brightness

00:23:47.060 --> 00:23:49.080
shows that they are
different, as well.

00:23:49.080 --> 00:23:52.310
So we were sort of stuck for
a while in the early 1990s

00:23:52.310 --> 00:23:56.840
until Mark Phillips and Mario
Hamuy developed a relationship.

00:23:56.840 --> 00:24:00.080
They found, by
looking at supernovae

00:24:00.080 --> 00:24:03.480
that are bright and nearby in
galaxies of known distance,

00:24:03.480 --> 00:24:06.420
that the intrinsically
more luminous ones

00:24:06.420 --> 00:24:10.670
decline more rapidly than
the less luminous ones.

00:24:10.670 --> 00:24:13.120
And we now know that they
rise more-- I'm sorry,

00:24:13.120 --> 00:24:15.850
decline more slowly is
what I meant to say.

00:24:15.850 --> 00:24:18.274
The luminous ones
decline more slowly

00:24:18.274 --> 00:24:19.440
than the less luminous ones.

00:24:19.440 --> 00:24:22.650
And we now know that they
rise more slowly, as well.

00:24:22.650 --> 00:24:24.900
So once you've determined
this relationship

00:24:24.900 --> 00:24:28.390
by using Type Ia supernovae
in galaxies of known distance,

00:24:28.390 --> 00:24:31.580
you can then apply it
to the distant ones,

00:24:31.580 --> 00:24:34.140
measure their light
curves, and figure out

00:24:34.140 --> 00:24:35.900
whether this is a
normal luminosity

00:24:35.900 --> 00:24:39.330
one, an over luminous one,
or a sub-luminous one.

00:24:39.330 --> 00:24:42.350
So instead of saying, these
are all 100-watt light bulbs,

00:24:42.350 --> 00:24:44.950
plus or minus 50 watts-- by
the way, they are much more

00:24:44.950 --> 00:24:46.450
luminous, of course--
you could say,

00:24:46.450 --> 00:24:49.340
this one is 116,
plus or minus 20,

00:24:49.340 --> 00:24:51.852
and, this one is 94,
plus or minus 12,

00:24:51.852 --> 00:24:52.810
or something like that.

00:24:52.810 --> 00:24:55.440
You can know where
in the distribution

00:24:55.440 --> 00:24:57.580
that particular
supernova comes from.

00:24:57.580 --> 00:24:59.520
And that is what
makes these things

00:24:59.520 --> 00:25:01.950
such great
standardizable candles.

00:25:01.950 --> 00:25:04.820
Sometimes astronomers call
them standard candles.

00:25:04.820 --> 00:25:06.090
But I don't like that term.

00:25:06.090 --> 00:25:07.980
Standardizable is better.

00:25:07.980 --> 00:25:09.560
So we find these things.

00:25:09.560 --> 00:25:11.830
My job on both teams
that did this work was

00:25:11.830 --> 00:25:14.160
to get spectra of them,
to get the redshifts

00:25:14.160 --> 00:25:16.585
and to make sure they
were Type Ia supernovae.

00:25:16.585 --> 00:25:19.620
I used the Keck
telescopes for that work.

00:25:19.620 --> 00:25:23.570
And here's then the diagram
of the possibilities.

00:25:23.570 --> 00:25:26.970
And here is what we
found, this green curve.

00:25:26.970 --> 00:25:27.770
OK.

00:25:27.770 --> 00:25:31.640
Oops, none of the above,
folks, the answer that's

00:25:31.640 --> 00:25:34.370
so attempting on
multiple choice exams.

00:25:34.370 --> 00:25:36.970
That's where the data fell.

00:25:36.970 --> 00:25:40.870
And if this is sort of a dense
universe-- 1, greater than 1,

00:25:40.870 --> 00:25:43.950
1.3, 0-- it doesn't
take a genius

00:25:43.950 --> 00:25:46.430
to realize that
this curve formally

00:25:46.430 --> 00:25:50.230
corresponds to a density
less than 0 for the universe.

00:25:50.230 --> 00:25:53.297
But that just doesn't
make any sense whatsoever,

00:25:53.297 --> 00:25:54.880
unless the other
parts of the universe

00:25:54.880 --> 00:25:57.500
are made out of some wacky
stuff with negative mass.

00:25:57.500 --> 00:25:59.380
But we have no
indication whatsoever

00:25:59.380 --> 00:26:00.479
that that's the case.

00:26:00.479 --> 00:26:02.020
Fortunately, there
is an alternative.

00:26:02.020 --> 00:26:03.395
There is what's
called Einstein's

00:26:03.395 --> 00:26:08.040
cosmological constant, which
now is just one subset of a more

00:26:08.040 --> 00:26:11.340
general class of theories
called dark energy theories,

00:26:11.340 --> 00:26:14.764
stuff that has a
positive energy density

00:26:14.764 --> 00:26:16.680
and actually has some
gravitational attraction

00:26:16.680 --> 00:26:18.360
associated with it,
but it has what's

00:26:18.360 --> 00:26:19.640
called a negative pressure.

00:26:19.640 --> 00:26:21.280
And the negative
pressure is what

00:26:21.280 --> 00:26:24.090
can accelerate the
expansion of the universe.

00:26:24.090 --> 00:26:26.520
So by the end of
'98, no one had found

00:26:26.520 --> 00:26:27.830
any flaws in what we had done.

00:26:27.830 --> 00:26:32.000
And so this was deemed by the
editors of "Science Magazine"

00:26:32.000 --> 00:26:34.120
as the single greatest
breakthrough in all areas

00:26:34.120 --> 00:26:35.131
of science that year.

00:26:35.131 --> 00:26:37.130
And so we were, obviously,
very pleased by that.

00:26:37.130 --> 00:26:39.027
And Einstein is
surprised here not

00:26:39.027 --> 00:26:40.610
because there are
multiple universes--

00:26:40.610 --> 00:26:41.569
though, there might be.

00:26:41.569 --> 00:26:42.985
Though, they don't
come from pipes

00:26:42.985 --> 00:26:44.240
of theoretical physicists.

00:26:44.240 --> 00:26:46.260
He's surprised because
this one universe

00:26:46.260 --> 00:26:49.240
is expanding at an
accelerating rate, rather

00:26:49.240 --> 00:26:50.560
than a decelerating rate.

00:26:50.560 --> 00:26:52.510
That's the bottom
line, is the data

00:26:52.510 --> 00:26:55.530
imply acceleration,
rather than deceleration.

00:26:55.530 --> 00:26:57.422
And that's just really weird.

00:26:57.422 --> 00:26:59.380
And when you combine the
supernova measurements

00:26:59.380 --> 00:27:01.700
with measurements of the
cosmic microwave background

00:27:01.700 --> 00:27:04.300
radiation and other data,
then you figure out,

00:27:04.300 --> 00:27:06.270
basically, that the
dark energy that

00:27:06.270 --> 00:27:09.181
is causing this repulsion,
whatever it is--

00:27:09.181 --> 00:27:10.930
and we don't know what
the dark energy is.

00:27:10.930 --> 00:27:13.310
It might be a property
of space itself,

00:27:13.310 --> 00:27:15.110
the cosmological
constant, or it could be

00:27:15.110 --> 00:27:16.860
some new kind of energy field.

00:27:16.860 --> 00:27:19.090
But whatever it is, it
actually constitutes

00:27:19.090 --> 00:27:22.000
70% of the total
contents of the universe.

00:27:22.000 --> 00:27:23.630
And we don't know what it is.

00:27:23.630 --> 00:27:26.020
And most of the
rest is dark matter

00:27:26.020 --> 00:27:28.620
that holds galaxies and
clusters of galaxies together.

00:27:28.620 --> 00:27:29.480
But we can't see it.

00:27:29.480 --> 00:27:31.480
And we don't know, really,
what that is, either.

00:27:31.480 --> 00:27:34.150
Although, it's probably
little, tiny particles

00:27:34.150 --> 00:27:35.350
left over from the Big Bang.

00:27:35.350 --> 00:27:36.410
But we're not sure.

00:27:36.410 --> 00:27:39.260
And the ordinary stuff, out
of which you and I and Google

00:27:39.260 --> 00:27:41.630
are made, is only 5%.

00:27:41.630 --> 00:27:43.870
And the easily visible stuff
is only half a percent.

00:27:43.870 --> 00:27:48.420
So if you're talking about
science to youngsters

00:27:48.420 --> 00:27:52.087
and someone says to you, well,
they heard from their uncle

00:27:52.087 --> 00:27:53.670
or something that
there's nothing left

00:27:53.670 --> 00:27:55.860
to be done in physics,
you tell that youngster,

00:27:55.860 --> 00:27:59.960
what about the origin and
nature of 95% of the universe?

00:27:59.960 --> 00:28:01.334
Pretty exciting stuff.

00:28:01.334 --> 00:28:03.000
And when I was a
student, we didn't even

00:28:03.000 --> 00:28:05.030
know that these parts
of the pie existed.

00:28:05.030 --> 00:28:07.150
The whole pie was
ordinary matter.

00:28:07.150 --> 00:28:09.765
And that consists of 92
naturally-occurring elements.

00:28:09.765 --> 00:28:10.510
OK.

00:28:10.510 --> 00:28:13.910
So anyway, this was all
confirmed in the subsequent 13

00:28:13.910 --> 00:28:19.430
years after 1998, at which
point the discovery was honored

00:28:19.430 --> 00:28:21.160
with a Nobel Prize in Physics.

00:28:21.160 --> 00:28:24.080
And given the rules, it went
to the team leaders, Sal

00:28:24.080 --> 00:28:26.730
Perlmutter at
Berkeley, Brian Schmidt

00:28:26.730 --> 00:28:28.740
at the Australian
National University--

00:28:28.740 --> 00:28:32.530
and I'm pleased to say that
the Nobel Committee did

00:28:32.530 --> 00:28:35.540
the right thing-- they gave
my post doctoral scholar, who

00:28:35.540 --> 00:28:37.110
was working with
me and with Brian,

00:28:37.110 --> 00:28:40.200
but directly under my mentorship
at Berkeley at the time

00:28:40.200 --> 00:28:41.840
that he made the
measurements-- He's

00:28:41.840 --> 00:28:43.500
the first on Schmidt's
team to realize

00:28:43.500 --> 00:28:44.990
what the data were telling us.

00:28:44.990 --> 00:28:47.619
These three gentlemen knew that
without the rest of us working

00:28:47.619 --> 00:28:50.160
in the trenches, they wouldn't
have been honored in this way.

00:28:50.160 --> 00:28:51.993
So they spent a good
fraction of their prize

00:28:51.993 --> 00:28:55.200
money flying the rest of us
out to celebrate Nobel Week.

00:28:55.200 --> 00:28:58.020
Here's right after the
awarding of the Nobel Prize

00:28:58.020 --> 00:28:59.110
to Schmidt and Riess.

00:28:59.110 --> 00:29:02.060
And here's the Supernova
Cosmology Project team.

00:29:02.060 --> 00:29:03.970
I happen not to be
in this picture,

00:29:03.970 --> 00:29:07.220
because their group picture
was taken right at the time

00:29:07.220 --> 00:29:09.220
that the high redshift
team, Schmidt's

00:29:09.220 --> 00:29:11.440
team, my primary
affiliation, was

00:29:11.440 --> 00:29:13.430
having its celebratory lunch.

00:29:13.430 --> 00:29:16.210
And at that lunch, Noelle,
my wife, who is here,

00:29:16.210 --> 00:29:19.660
revealed a t-shirt
that she made--

00:29:19.660 --> 00:29:21.410
"Dark energy is the new black."

00:29:21.410 --> 00:29:23.770
And that was our
consolation prize

00:29:23.770 --> 00:29:26.290
for not winning the
Nobel Prize itself,

00:29:26.290 --> 00:29:28.030
but for having done the work.

00:29:28.030 --> 00:29:30.890
And that was really the thrill,
is just having done the work.

00:29:30.890 --> 00:29:33.080
And never in my
wildest dreams as a kid

00:29:33.080 --> 00:29:34.870
did I think that I
would be associated

00:29:34.870 --> 00:29:35.820
with such a discovery.

00:29:35.820 --> 00:29:37.650
And so that's been
the real reward.

00:29:37.650 --> 00:29:40.297
It's just been the fun and
working with people and stuff.

00:29:40.297 --> 00:29:42.130
Nevertheless, it is
nice to get some credit.

00:29:42.130 --> 00:29:44.660
And as Alvaro said,
more recently,

00:29:44.660 --> 00:29:47.600
the 2015 Breakthrough Prize
in Fundamental Physics

00:29:47.600 --> 00:29:52.010
specifically by name recognized
all of the participants, all 51

00:29:52.010 --> 00:29:52.510
of them.

00:29:52.510 --> 00:29:53.610
And so that's really good.

00:29:53.610 --> 00:29:54.250
So there we go.

00:29:54.250 --> 00:29:54.340
Yeah.

00:29:54.340 --> 00:29:54.910
[LAUGHTER]

00:29:54.910 --> 00:29:59.460
So anyway, specifically,
the Lick contributions

00:29:59.460 --> 00:30:03.980
were in the early 1990s showing
the spectroscopic diversity

00:30:03.980 --> 00:30:05.950
of Type Ia supernovae.

00:30:05.950 --> 00:30:08.390
And then in the years
following the building

00:30:08.390 --> 00:30:10.850
of the Katzman
telescope in 1998,

00:30:10.850 --> 00:30:13.060
getting lots and lots of
light curves and stuff

00:30:13.060 --> 00:30:17.310
and verifying this,
admittedly, not yet

00:30:17.310 --> 00:30:20.650
well-verified discovery
that we announced in 1998.

00:30:20.650 --> 00:30:22.500
At some point, you've
just got to be brave.

00:30:22.500 --> 00:30:23.940
And if you think
you've done your work,

00:30:23.940 --> 00:30:25.220
you have to announce
a discovery,

00:30:25.220 --> 00:30:27.303
even though you're not
sure that you're right yet.

00:30:27.303 --> 00:30:30.580
But the confirmation
of this light curve

00:30:30.580 --> 00:30:33.380
shape versus luminosity
relationship with the Katzman

00:30:33.380 --> 00:30:37.180
telescope, so that
was something we did.

00:30:37.180 --> 00:30:41.460
Next big topic-- and one that I
personally don't work on, just

00:30:41.460 --> 00:30:44.300
to show you that I'm really
being fair and egalitarian here

00:30:44.300 --> 00:30:48.290
and stuff-- exoplanets, really
a hot field in astrophysics

00:30:48.290 --> 00:30:48.790
these days.

00:30:48.790 --> 00:30:51.400
Basically, are there
other planetary systems?

00:30:51.400 --> 00:30:53.630
Are any of them like
our own solar system?

00:30:53.630 --> 00:30:55.840
Well, the way to
detect exoplanets

00:30:55.840 --> 00:30:58.690
is not so much to see
their reflected light--

00:30:58.690 --> 00:31:00.890
because they're so dim
they're lost in the glare--

00:31:00.890 --> 00:31:03.630
but rather to see the
effect they have on the star

00:31:03.630 --> 00:31:05.210
that they orbit,
or, more correctly,

00:31:05.210 --> 00:31:07.610
the two orbit their
common center of mass.

00:31:07.610 --> 00:31:10.640
So when the planet is
going away from us,

00:31:10.640 --> 00:31:12.680
the star will be
going toward us.

00:31:12.680 --> 00:31:14.640
And the light will
be blueshifted--

00:31:14.640 --> 00:31:16.432
by the way, not
instantaneously, of course.

00:31:16.432 --> 00:31:18.848
But the blueshifted part will
travel at the speed of light

00:31:18.848 --> 00:31:19.540
toward us.

00:31:19.540 --> 00:31:20.940
That's a bit of a subtlety here.

00:31:20.940 --> 00:31:23.216
But anyway, no big deal.

00:31:23.216 --> 00:31:24.840
And when the planet
is going toward us,

00:31:24.840 --> 00:31:26.339
the star will be
going away from us.

00:31:26.339 --> 00:31:28.727
And so you'll see these
periodic Doppler shifts.

00:31:28.727 --> 00:31:31.060
And you have to spread out
the spectrum a heck of a lot.

00:31:31.060 --> 00:31:32.830
So it's a high
dispersion spectrograph.

00:31:32.830 --> 00:31:34.680
And let's zoom in
on it and see what's

00:31:34.680 --> 00:31:36.400
happening to these
absorption lines.

00:31:36.400 --> 00:31:38.020
So here's a little
magnifying glass.

00:31:38.020 --> 00:31:40.353
And we're going to look at
the absorption lines produced

00:31:40.353 --> 00:31:42.760
by the chemical elements in
the atmosphere of the star.

00:31:42.760 --> 00:31:44.310
They shift back and forth.

00:31:44.310 --> 00:31:47.000
And you can measure
the changing flux

00:31:47.000 --> 00:31:48.790
levels in these little pixels.

00:31:48.790 --> 00:31:52.400
And the shifts are typically
1/1,000 of a pixel.

00:31:52.400 --> 00:31:54.650
So we've exaggerated
the effect a lot here.

00:31:54.650 --> 00:31:56.660
But there are thousands
of absorption lines.

00:31:56.660 --> 00:31:58.920
If you use cross-correlation
techniques and stuff,

00:31:58.920 --> 00:32:02.960
you can measure speeds
that are basically walking

00:32:02.960 --> 00:32:04.700
speed, meters per second.

00:32:04.700 --> 00:32:05.800
It's unbelievable.

00:32:05.800 --> 00:32:07.630
They're now down to
a meter per second.

00:32:07.630 --> 00:32:09.950
But you need huge
amounts of time,

00:32:09.950 --> 00:32:14.760
or on modest-size telescopes
to get enough data, right?

00:32:14.760 --> 00:32:18.230
Measuring the star once or twice
is just not going to do it.

00:32:18.230 --> 00:32:21.820
So here in the early 1990s,
Geoff Marcy and Paul Butler

00:32:21.820 --> 00:32:24.570
using the Lick 3-meter telescope
made some measurements.

00:32:24.570 --> 00:32:28.160
They noticed that the star
wasn't standing still.

00:32:28.160 --> 00:32:30.640
And here's a periodic
function fit through it.

00:32:30.640 --> 00:32:33.930
But they said, well, let's start
taking data more frequently,

00:32:33.930 --> 00:32:35.180
and then really frequently.

00:32:35.180 --> 00:32:39.440
And you can see that there is
sort of a 0.7-year variability

00:32:39.440 --> 00:32:45.150
here in the velocity and
also a 4-year variability.

00:32:45.150 --> 00:32:48.390
And a 4.6-day variability
has been removed from this

00:32:48.390 --> 00:32:49.840
presentation of the data.

00:32:49.840 --> 00:32:54.670
So Epsilon Andromedae has this
three-planet system where there

00:32:54.670 --> 00:32:58.060
is this 4-Jupiter-mass planet
way out here with a 4-year

00:32:58.060 --> 00:33:01.250
period-- the 4s
are coincidental--

00:33:01.250 --> 00:33:04.644
the 2-Jupiter-mass planet
with a period of 0.7 years,

00:33:04.644 --> 00:33:06.810
and then this little guy
here, which is actually not

00:33:06.810 --> 00:33:10.330
so little, half a Jupiter mass
or so, with a 4.6-day orbital

00:33:10.330 --> 00:33:11.090
period.

00:33:11.090 --> 00:33:15.500
This is the beginning of
a very exciting new class

00:33:15.500 --> 00:33:17.350
of planets called hot Jupiters.

00:33:17.350 --> 00:33:19.570
This thing basically
has the mass of Jupiter,

00:33:19.570 --> 00:33:22.480
yet it's orbiting the star
with an orbital period

00:33:22.480 --> 00:33:24.709
of just a few days.

00:33:24.709 --> 00:33:26.000
It shouldn't have formed there.

00:33:26.000 --> 00:33:28.130
Jupiter is a big,
gaseous, liquid thing.

00:33:28.130 --> 00:33:30.520
Probably, it formed farther
out and then migrated in

00:33:30.520 --> 00:33:32.090
through friction
with the accretion

00:33:32.090 --> 00:33:34.290
with the protoplanetary
disk or something.

00:33:34.290 --> 00:33:36.640
But here's an artist's
impression of it.

00:33:36.640 --> 00:33:38.470
It may even be evaporating away.

00:33:38.470 --> 00:33:40.870
We have evidence of ones
that are evaporating away.

00:33:40.870 --> 00:33:42.420
Obviously, we don't
have any pictures

00:33:42.420 --> 00:33:43.590
that are quite like this.

00:33:43.590 --> 00:33:45.957
But if anyone wants to
help build a telescope,

00:33:45.957 --> 00:33:46.790
if that's-- Anyway--

00:33:46.790 --> 00:33:47.980
[LAUGHTER]

00:33:47.980 --> 00:33:50.170
So anyway, you might
wonder, how do you

00:33:50.170 --> 00:33:55.130
get actual parameters like the
orbital distance and the mass?

00:33:55.130 --> 00:33:58.230
So here's 51 Pegasi,
the one that was first

00:33:58.230 --> 00:34:00.480
found by a team of
Swiss astronomers

00:34:00.480 --> 00:34:04.060
and then quickly verified
by Marcy and Butler.

00:34:04.060 --> 00:34:07.370
Again, a 4.23-day
period in this case.

00:34:07.370 --> 00:34:11.040
Well, the period is
4.23 days for 51 Pegasi

00:34:11.040 --> 00:34:12.595
b, this little exoplanet.

00:34:12.595 --> 00:34:14.469
Kepler's law is that
the square of the period

00:34:14.469 --> 00:34:16.610
is proportional to the
cube of the distance,

00:34:16.610 --> 00:34:19.389
and you have to divide
by the mass of the star.

00:34:19.389 --> 00:34:22.380
Oh, and by the way, the
constant of proportionality

00:34:22.380 --> 00:34:24.679
is 1 when you use
these particular units.

00:34:24.679 --> 00:34:27.700
You know the mass of the
star from its classification.

00:34:27.700 --> 00:34:29.550
We know stars
pretty well by now.

00:34:29.550 --> 00:34:31.420
So you can solve for
R. And in this case,

00:34:31.420 --> 00:34:35.750
it's 1/20 of Earth's orbital
distance from the sun.

00:34:35.750 --> 00:34:39.630
So this guy is just
screaming around this star

00:34:39.630 --> 00:34:43.790
with a mass of 0.45
Jupiter's divided by sine i.

00:34:43.790 --> 00:34:46.909
And the factor of the sign
of the inclination angle

00:34:46.909 --> 00:34:50.780
is that you don't know what
the orbital inclination is

00:34:50.780 --> 00:34:51.889
to your line of sight.

00:34:51.889 --> 00:34:54.303
The really nice ones are the
ones that are 90 degrees.

00:34:54.303 --> 00:34:55.969
They're transiting
the Kepler satellite.

00:34:55.969 --> 00:34:56.856
Found some of those.

00:34:56.856 --> 00:34:58.730
There, you know that
the angle is 90 degrees.

00:34:58.730 --> 00:35:00.270
So sine of i is 1.

00:35:00.270 --> 00:35:02.480
But where you don't
know, you're only

00:35:02.480 --> 00:35:05.710
seeing in the Doppler
effect, that component

00:35:05.710 --> 00:35:07.674
of the total velocity,
which is radial.

00:35:07.674 --> 00:35:09.090
You don't see the
transverse part.

00:35:09.090 --> 00:35:12.441
And that's why you get only
a lower limit for the mass.

00:35:12.441 --> 00:35:12.940
OK.

00:35:12.940 --> 00:35:16.180
So let's get the mass
now knowing the distance.

00:35:16.180 --> 00:35:19.700
So there we go.

00:35:19.700 --> 00:35:21.910
Conservation of
momentum-- M star V star

00:35:21.910 --> 00:35:23.230
is M planet V planet.

00:35:23.230 --> 00:35:25.955
The overall system is
just sitting there.

00:35:25.955 --> 00:35:27.400
Solve for the mass
of the planet.

00:35:27.400 --> 00:35:28.530
There we go.

00:35:28.530 --> 00:35:31.510
You know the mass of the
star from its classification.

00:35:31.510 --> 00:35:34.680
You get the speed of the star
from the maximum Doppler shift,

00:35:34.680 --> 00:35:37.720
55 meters per
second in this case.

00:35:37.720 --> 00:35:39.830
What is the speed of the planet?

00:35:39.830 --> 00:35:43.760
Well, I'll just do it
for circular orbits here.

00:35:43.760 --> 00:35:46.780
Circumference--
that total distance

00:35:46.780 --> 00:35:48.420
is the speed times the period.

00:35:48.420 --> 00:35:48.920
OK.

00:35:48.920 --> 00:35:51.820
And so you can solve for
the speed of the planet.

00:35:51.820 --> 00:35:54.274
And you know R. I just did
that on the previous slide.

00:35:54.274 --> 00:35:56.440
So the mass of the planet
in this case is about half

00:35:56.440 --> 00:35:57.050
a Jupiter mass.

00:35:57.050 --> 00:35:57.830
So that's how you do it.

00:35:57.830 --> 00:36:00.250
For elliptical orbits, it's a
little bit more complicated.

00:36:00.250 --> 00:36:02.166
So the other big surprise
early on in the game

00:36:02.166 --> 00:36:05.740
was that instead of just having
nearly circular, only slightly

00:36:05.740 --> 00:36:08.040
eccentric orbits, as
in our solar system,

00:36:08.040 --> 00:36:11.240
a whole bunch of exoplanets
were found with these highly

00:36:11.240 --> 00:36:12.360
eccentric orbits.

00:36:12.360 --> 00:36:14.090
And the signature
of such an orbit

00:36:14.090 --> 00:36:17.360
is where you have a
periodic velocity curve,

00:36:17.360 --> 00:36:18.800
but it is not sinusoidal.

00:36:18.800 --> 00:36:19.300
OK.

00:36:19.300 --> 00:36:20.640
So this is clearly periodic.

00:36:20.640 --> 00:36:24.240
But what's happening
is the star's speed

00:36:24.240 --> 00:36:26.300
reverses very, very quickly.

00:36:26.300 --> 00:36:28.040
And that's, of course,
when the planet

00:36:28.040 --> 00:36:29.430
goes zipping around the star.

00:36:29.430 --> 00:36:33.000
The star's speed reverses very
quickly at that moment, too,

00:36:33.000 --> 00:36:35.701
because it goes
[VOCALIZING    ENGINE].

00:36:35.701 --> 00:36:37.450
And that's Kepler's
second law, of course.

00:36:37.450 --> 00:36:40.750
So anyway, who among
you were students

00:36:40.750 --> 00:36:42.220
in my Astro 10 class at Cal?

00:36:42.220 --> 00:36:43.591
I know several of you were.

00:36:43.591 --> 00:36:45.590
OK, so I'm going to quiz
you on this afterwards.

00:36:45.590 --> 00:36:46.470
You'd better remember.

00:36:46.470 --> 00:36:47.850
Otherwise, you'll
fail the class.

00:36:47.850 --> 00:36:51.291
And your job at Google
will have been revoked.

00:36:51.291 --> 00:36:51.790
OK.

00:36:51.790 --> 00:36:55.019
So the big thing in the
early days-- and it's still

00:36:55.019 --> 00:36:57.310
interesting that more of
these things are being found--

00:36:57.310 --> 00:37:02.020
are lots of hot Jupiters and
lots of these eccentric ones.

00:37:02.020 --> 00:37:04.190
Of course, more normal
ones have been found.

00:37:04.190 --> 00:37:06.600
And the Kepler satellite
has been wonderful recently

00:37:06.600 --> 00:37:08.660
at finding transiting ones.

00:37:08.660 --> 00:37:11.660
But in the early days,
especially Paul Butler

00:37:11.660 --> 00:37:14.990
and Geoff Marcy-- Marcy's
a professor at Berkeley--

00:37:14.990 --> 00:37:17.370
were the undisputed
leaders in this field.

00:37:17.370 --> 00:37:21.330
They found 70 of the first
100 known exoplanets.

00:37:21.330 --> 00:37:23.630
And they did it with the
Lick 3-meter telescope.

00:37:23.630 --> 00:37:25.240
And that's still a
relevant telescope.

00:37:25.240 --> 00:37:27.670
And they still are
among the leaders.

00:37:27.670 --> 00:37:30.970
But back then, they found
most of these things.

00:37:30.970 --> 00:37:33.660
And in the early
'90s-- well, mid

00:37:33.660 --> 00:37:36.810
'90s, in this case-- when
two planets were found,

00:37:36.810 --> 00:37:38.880
it made the cover
of "Time Magazine."

00:37:38.880 --> 00:37:40.750
You know, "Dole
Drops, Clinton Rises."

00:37:40.750 --> 00:37:43.230
Well, half of this might be
relevant for the next year

00:37:43.230 --> 00:37:43.960
and a half or so.

00:37:43.960 --> 00:37:45.810
But anyway, "Is
Anybody Out There?--

00:37:45.810 --> 00:37:47.560
How the Discovery of
Two Planets Brings Us

00:37:47.560 --> 00:37:49.351
Closer to Solving the
Most Profound Mystery

00:37:49.351 --> 00:37:49.990
in the Cosmos."

00:37:49.990 --> 00:37:51.406
You know, is there
life out there?

00:37:51.406 --> 00:37:53.640
Is there intelligent life?

00:37:53.640 --> 00:37:55.839
You might say we already
have published evidence

00:37:55.839 --> 00:37:58.380
that there really is, of course,
because look-- "Weekly World

00:37:58.380 --> 00:38:00.190
News," "Alien Backs
Arnold for Governor."

00:38:00.190 --> 00:38:01.720
I don't have to tell
this crowd not to believe

00:38:01.720 --> 00:38:03.011
everything you read, of course.

00:38:03.011 --> 00:38:05.520
So anyway, so a lot of
those were hot Jupiters.

00:38:05.520 --> 00:38:07.470
Here's Lynette Cook's
artist's impression

00:38:07.470 --> 00:38:09.310
of what one of these
things looks like.

00:38:09.310 --> 00:38:12.600
But the name of the game now
is we want to find Earths.

00:38:12.600 --> 00:38:15.940
And we want to find Earths in
the habitable or potentially

00:38:15.940 --> 00:38:18.620
habitable zone, where
liquid water might exist

00:38:18.620 --> 00:38:20.240
on the surface of the planet.

00:38:20.240 --> 00:38:22.590
So for that, you need
really huge amounts

00:38:22.590 --> 00:38:24.460
of time on modest-size
telescopes,

00:38:24.460 --> 00:38:27.340
because though
Jupiter would produce

00:38:27.340 --> 00:38:31.730
a signal of about 10
meters per second--

00:38:31.730 --> 00:38:34.760
if an alien were looking at
the sun, they would see the sun

00:38:34.760 --> 00:38:37.050
moving around at a speed
of 10 meters per second

00:38:37.050 --> 00:38:39.300
because of Jupiter.

00:38:39.300 --> 00:38:41.370
The reflex motion
caused by Earth

00:38:41.370 --> 00:38:44.610
is 10 centimeters per second.

00:38:44.610 --> 00:38:48.110
So that's the motion of
the sun induced by Earth.

00:38:48.110 --> 00:38:50.320
So you really need a
lot of telescope time

00:38:50.320 --> 00:38:52.490
to dig the signal
out of the noise.

00:38:52.490 --> 00:38:54.240
And so Marcy said,
you, Filippenko, you're

00:38:54.240 --> 00:38:57.410
using up too much of the 3-meter
for your studies of supernovae.

00:38:57.410 --> 00:39:00.805
So he built himself, along
with Steve Vogt at Santa Cruz,

00:39:00.805 --> 00:39:04.480
a 2.4-meter telescope, the
size of the Hubble, basically,

00:39:04.480 --> 00:39:07.170
that's dedicated to
looking for planets.

00:39:07.170 --> 00:39:10.590
And so they're looking at the
brightest stars in the sky.

00:39:10.590 --> 00:39:13.540
Sure everyone would like
the Lick's sky to be darker,

00:39:13.540 --> 00:39:16.460
but it's not necessary
for all types of projects.

00:39:16.460 --> 00:39:17.480
And we live here.

00:39:17.480 --> 00:39:19.190
And that's just the way it goes.

00:39:19.190 --> 00:39:20.842
But for naked-eye
stars, you hardly

00:39:20.842 --> 00:39:23.300
care about the sky brightness,
as long as the sun isn't up.

00:39:23.300 --> 00:39:25.175
And so, you know, I'm
being a bit facetious.

00:39:25.175 --> 00:39:27.050
But the point is you
can do this kind of work

00:39:27.050 --> 00:39:30.210
over and over again, look
at the same stars searching

00:39:30.210 --> 00:39:31.830
for Earth-like planets.

00:39:31.830 --> 00:39:34.650
And here's Lauren Weiss,
one of our grad students,

00:39:34.650 --> 00:39:36.660
running this whole
system from Berkeley.

00:39:36.660 --> 00:39:37.880
And in fact, it's robotic.

00:39:37.880 --> 00:39:40.230
So really, what she's doing
is looking at the data

00:39:40.230 --> 00:39:43.050
as the data are coming in,
monitoring for quality control,

00:39:43.050 --> 00:39:45.340
that kind of thing, because
these systems are now

00:39:45.340 --> 00:39:46.270
largely robotic.

00:39:46.270 --> 00:39:49.220
And the project
they're doing now

00:39:49.220 --> 00:39:51.740
is to search for
Earth-like planets

00:39:51.740 --> 00:39:56.350
among the nearest stars, the
roughly 100 stars that are

00:39:56.350 --> 00:39:58.300
within about 20 light years.

00:39:58.300 --> 00:40:01.150
Because if we can find
Earth-like exoplanets

00:40:01.150 --> 00:40:04.980
around those stars, well, that
might be a post, a signpost,

00:40:04.980 --> 00:40:08.581
of where to look
if we seek Yoda.

00:40:08.581 --> 00:40:09.080
All right.

00:40:09.080 --> 00:40:13.590
Supermassive black holes,
my next science topic.

00:40:13.590 --> 00:40:15.420
A black hole is a
region where gravity

00:40:15.420 --> 00:40:18.400
is so strong that nothing,
not even light, can escape.

00:40:18.400 --> 00:40:20.290
So apples can't escape.

00:40:20.290 --> 00:40:21.620
Rockets can't escape.

00:40:21.620 --> 00:40:23.180
Not even light can escape.

00:40:23.180 --> 00:40:26.470
So here is my prize-winning
photograph of a black hole.

00:40:26.470 --> 00:40:29.030
Yeah, you can just
choose a black background

00:40:29.030 --> 00:40:31.850
in PowerPoint, or whatever,
put your lens cap on.

00:40:31.850 --> 00:40:34.020
"Abandon all hope,
ye who enter here!!,"

00:40:34.020 --> 00:40:36.710
quoting from "Dante's
Inferno," of course.

00:40:36.710 --> 00:40:37.920
They're pretty wild places.

00:40:37.920 --> 00:40:39.840
They suck you in, and
they don't let you out.

00:40:39.840 --> 00:40:41.670
So they're pretty ferocious.

00:40:41.670 --> 00:40:43.930
We have a saying, what
happens in a black hole

00:40:43.930 --> 00:40:46.111
stays in a black hole.

00:40:46.111 --> 00:40:46.610
All right.

00:40:46.610 --> 00:40:48.735
Well, how do you detect
them if you don't see them?

00:40:48.735 --> 00:40:50.550
Again, by their
gravitational influence.

00:40:50.550 --> 00:40:53.230
This is essentially
like exoplanets.

00:40:53.230 --> 00:40:55.170
You can measure the
mass of an object.

00:40:55.170 --> 00:40:57.270
If you measure the
distance of something

00:40:57.270 --> 00:41:00.570
orbiting it and
the orbital speed.

00:41:00.570 --> 00:41:08.230
In the case of exoplanets, what
we used was a period and speed.

00:41:08.230 --> 00:41:09.920
And from that, we
got R. But as long

00:41:09.920 --> 00:41:11.580
as you have two of
those variables,

00:41:11.580 --> 00:41:13.740
you get the third one,
and you can get M.

00:41:13.740 --> 00:41:16.050
Anyway, we suspected
for a long time

00:41:16.050 --> 00:41:20.580
that big black holes might
exist within an active galaxy.

00:41:20.580 --> 00:41:23.040
And an active galaxy
is like a normal galaxy

00:41:23.040 --> 00:41:26.110
that has a concentration of
brightness near the center.

00:41:26.110 --> 00:41:27.800
But in an active
galaxy, the center

00:41:27.800 --> 00:41:30.540
is unusually bright, as though
something very energetic

00:41:30.540 --> 00:41:31.994
is going on inside.

00:41:31.994 --> 00:41:34.160
And you might think, why
would that be a black hole?

00:41:34.160 --> 00:41:35.590
I just told you
that a black hole

00:41:35.590 --> 00:41:38.410
is a region from which
light does not escape.

00:41:38.410 --> 00:41:38.990
That's true.

00:41:38.990 --> 00:41:41.640
But if you have a black hole,
especially if it's spinning,

00:41:41.640 --> 00:41:43.710
and you've got an
accretion disk orbiting it,

00:41:43.710 --> 00:41:45.720
then in the process
of falling in,

00:41:45.720 --> 00:41:48.740
that material rubs against
neighboring material

00:41:48.740 --> 00:41:52.480
and converts its
gravitational potential energy

00:41:52.480 --> 00:41:55.890
and its bulk kinetic
energy into light.

00:41:55.890 --> 00:41:59.560
And that can be a very
efficient process,

00:41:59.560 --> 00:42:02.340
10 times more efficient than
nuclear energy, by the way.

00:42:02.340 --> 00:42:05.100
So that might be a place
where there is a black hole,

00:42:05.100 --> 00:42:07.740
because you need a very
efficient release of energy

00:42:07.740 --> 00:42:10.612
from a small region in the
middle of an active galaxy.

00:42:10.612 --> 00:42:12.820
So how do you prove that
there is a black hole there?

00:42:12.820 --> 00:42:15.620
Well, here is the spectrum of
light from an active galaxy.

00:42:15.620 --> 00:42:17.060
And you have several components.

00:42:17.060 --> 00:42:20.120
Here's the continuum that
comes from this accretion

00:42:20.120 --> 00:42:21.420
disk of material.

00:42:21.420 --> 00:42:23.230
And then you have
these emission lines.

00:42:23.230 --> 00:42:27.350
And the emission lines come in
two forms-- narrow and broad.

00:42:27.350 --> 00:42:28.850
Here's some narrow ones.

00:42:28.850 --> 00:42:31.070
They come from gas
that's relatively far

00:42:31.070 --> 00:42:32.320
from the putative black hole.

00:42:32.320 --> 00:42:34.520
And that gas isn't
moving very quickly.

00:42:34.520 --> 00:42:37.140
But there's also these
broad Balmer lines

00:42:37.140 --> 00:42:39.590
of hydrogen, which
come from gas that's

00:42:39.590 --> 00:42:41.540
moving with speeds of
thousands of kilometers

00:42:41.540 --> 00:42:46.120
per second very near
the putative black hole.

00:42:46.120 --> 00:42:47.980
Well, so here's
sort of an anatomy

00:42:47.980 --> 00:42:49.950
of an active galactic nucleus.

00:42:49.950 --> 00:42:50.950
There is the black hole.

00:42:50.950 --> 00:42:54.100
There is the accretion disk that
emits the continuum radiation.

00:42:54.100 --> 00:42:57.030
Here is this broad line
region where clouds of gas

00:42:57.030 --> 00:43:00.130
are moving around very quickly,
producing those broad lines,

00:43:00.130 --> 00:43:01.719
because some gas
is Doppler-shifted

00:43:01.719 --> 00:43:03.010
because it's moving toward you.

00:43:03.010 --> 00:43:05.350
Some of it is
Doppler-redshifted because it's

00:43:05.350 --> 00:43:07.360
moving away from you.

00:43:07.360 --> 00:43:09.190
That's what gives the breadth.

00:43:09.190 --> 00:43:13.799
So if you can measure the
motions of these clouds

00:43:13.799 --> 00:43:15.340
and if there is some
way to determine

00:43:15.340 --> 00:43:18.750
their distance from the
center, well, that's

00:43:18.750 --> 00:43:20.070
a speed and a distance.

00:43:20.070 --> 00:43:22.530
That's what you need
to get the mass.

00:43:22.530 --> 00:43:26.030
Remember from that thing
that I just showed.

00:43:26.030 --> 00:43:26.570
All right.

00:43:26.570 --> 00:43:29.110
So well, the width
of the broad line--

00:43:29.110 --> 00:43:30.680
here is hydrogen
data-- tells you

00:43:30.680 --> 00:43:33.530
something about the aggregate
orbital speeds of the clouds

00:43:33.530 --> 00:43:35.190
in this broad line region.

00:43:35.190 --> 00:43:38.000
And if you measure how far these
clouds are from the black hole,

00:43:38.000 --> 00:43:41.770
then you've got what you
need to solve for the mass.

00:43:41.770 --> 00:43:43.430
Well, how do we do that?

00:43:43.430 --> 00:43:45.270
We use a technique
called echo mapping.

00:43:45.270 --> 00:43:46.130
Here's a nebula.

00:43:46.130 --> 00:43:47.580
This is called a
planetary nebula.

00:43:47.580 --> 00:43:48.996
It has nothing to
do with planets.

00:43:48.996 --> 00:43:52.780
But our own sun will do this
in about 5 or 6 billion years,

00:43:52.780 --> 00:43:55.570
when it becomes a red
giant and the outer parts

00:43:55.570 --> 00:43:58.270
of its atmosphere will
be only loosely held.

00:43:58.270 --> 00:44:00.960
So the point is there
is a hot star here.

00:44:00.960 --> 00:44:04.530
And if you've got
ultraviolet radiation coming

00:44:04.530 --> 00:44:07.590
from that hot star
or some other source,

00:44:07.590 --> 00:44:10.080
then it will ionize
the clouds of gas.

00:44:10.080 --> 00:44:12.670
And if you have an increase
in the UV brightness

00:44:12.670 --> 00:44:16.610
of this source, that will lead
to an increase in the emission

00:44:16.610 --> 00:44:19.750
line brightness of the
surrounding ionized gas.

00:44:19.750 --> 00:44:22.000
But if you're over
here somewhere,

00:44:22.000 --> 00:44:24.070
it will have taken
time for light

00:44:24.070 --> 00:44:27.530
to travel to the back side
and produce emission lines

00:44:27.530 --> 00:44:29.260
and then to reach you.

00:44:29.260 --> 00:44:32.440
Whereas from the front side,
the continuum variation

00:44:32.440 --> 00:44:34.260
and the emission
line variation will

00:44:34.260 --> 00:44:36.250
be essentially simultaneous.

00:44:36.250 --> 00:44:39.090
So the observer will
see a time delay

00:44:39.090 --> 00:44:40.750
between changes
in the brightness

00:44:40.750 --> 00:44:42.920
of the central source
and the brightness

00:44:42.920 --> 00:44:44.540
of the overall nebula.

00:44:44.540 --> 00:44:46.800
Different parts will
brighten at different times.

00:44:46.800 --> 00:44:48.870
But if they're
spatially unresolved,

00:44:48.870 --> 00:44:51.040
it just means there
will be an overall delay

00:44:51.040 --> 00:44:53.070
in the brightening
of this nebula.

00:44:53.070 --> 00:44:56.730
So if we look at, say, a
step function continuum

00:44:56.730 --> 00:44:59.520
variation of the
active nucleus, it

00:44:59.520 --> 00:45:01.960
might look
intrinsically like this.

00:45:01.960 --> 00:45:04.310
But the emission
line light curve

00:45:04.310 --> 00:45:06.740
will start brightening
at the time

00:45:06.740 --> 00:45:09.460
that the continuum brightened
because the emission line

00:45:09.460 --> 00:45:11.150
clouds that are along
the line of sight

00:45:11.150 --> 00:45:14.190
to the continuum source suffer
essentially no time delay.

00:45:14.190 --> 00:45:16.420
But there will be a
progressively bigger and bigger

00:45:16.420 --> 00:45:18.540
time delay for all
these clouds here.

00:45:18.540 --> 00:45:23.130
And so the overall thing will
have this kind of a shape.

00:45:23.130 --> 00:45:26.390
And that's how you get a measure
of the size of the system.

00:45:26.390 --> 00:45:28.780
So we measure the
continuum light curves

00:45:28.780 --> 00:45:31.440
with a telescope
like KAIT, where

00:45:31.440 --> 00:45:33.170
you can get many,
many measurements

00:45:33.170 --> 00:45:34.710
over the course of time.

00:45:34.710 --> 00:45:37.260
We measure the
emission line light

00:45:37.260 --> 00:45:39.310
curves using a bigger
telescope, because you

00:45:39.310 --> 00:45:41.330
have to spread the light
out into a spectrum

00:45:41.330 --> 00:45:44.720
and measure the
individual emission lines.

00:45:44.720 --> 00:45:47.200
But the point is you need
huge amounts of time, right?

00:45:47.200 --> 00:45:48.699
You're not going
to do this with one

00:45:48.699 --> 00:45:51.220
or two measurements on the
world's biggest telescopes.

00:45:51.220 --> 00:45:56.430
This should be firmly affixed
to your brain at this point

00:45:56.430 --> 00:45:57.390
through your retina.

00:45:57.390 --> 00:46:00.050
And again, students and
postdocs are doing all this work

00:46:00.050 --> 00:46:03.190
remotely from the UC campuses.

00:46:03.190 --> 00:46:04.120
It's really great.

00:46:04.120 --> 00:46:09.320
So what we've found for a
bunch of studies of galaxies--

00:46:09.320 --> 00:46:13.180
and this overall study is led
by Aaron Barth of UC Irvine,

00:46:13.180 --> 00:46:17.300
who is a former PhD student
of mine-- is we indeed

00:46:17.300 --> 00:46:19.800
find evidence, as have
other astronomers-- again,

00:46:19.800 --> 00:46:22.430
none of what I'm saying
is unique to our group.

00:46:22.430 --> 00:46:24.410
But what we found
is there really

00:46:24.410 --> 00:46:28.060
are big black holes in the
centers of these galaxies,

00:46:28.060 --> 00:46:30.570
as shown by these data
that we've gathered.

00:46:30.570 --> 00:46:33.800
And so this theoretical picture
that was proposed 50 years ago

00:46:33.800 --> 00:46:35.070
appears to be correct.

00:46:35.070 --> 00:46:38.690
And Einstein never thought
that black holes actually

00:46:38.690 --> 00:46:39.850
occur in nature.

00:46:39.850 --> 00:46:42.630
He was aware that they are a
possible theoretical prediction

00:46:42.630 --> 00:46:44.910
consistent with his general
theory of relativity.

00:46:44.910 --> 00:46:46.600
But he didn't think
that nature has

00:46:46.600 --> 00:46:48.140
any way of making black holes.

00:46:48.140 --> 00:46:51.050
Well, imagine what his reaction
would be if he were alive now

00:46:51.050 --> 00:46:53.480
and could see the evidence
that we and others have

00:46:53.480 --> 00:46:54.730
found for black holes.

00:46:54.730 --> 00:46:57.860
I mean, his reaction might
be something like this.

00:46:57.860 --> 00:46:59.820
Finally, technology development.

00:46:59.820 --> 00:47:01.260
There, we do lots of things.

00:47:01.260 --> 00:47:05.810
We make and test new equipment
on smaller telescopes,

00:47:05.810 --> 00:47:07.330
where the time
isn't so precious.

00:47:07.330 --> 00:47:09.520
And then we move it over
to other telescopes.

00:47:09.520 --> 00:47:12.310
And the one application
I want to focus on,

00:47:12.310 --> 00:47:15.680
given limited time, is laser
guide star adaptive optics.

00:47:15.680 --> 00:47:17.680
When you look at stars
through a telescope,

00:47:17.680 --> 00:47:18.826
they look smeared out.

00:47:18.826 --> 00:47:20.200
And this is related
to twinkling,

00:47:20.200 --> 00:47:22.167
because the different
light rays are

00:47:22.167 --> 00:47:24.500
passing through different
pockets in Earth's atmosphere,

00:47:24.500 --> 00:47:26.610
having different
indices of refraction

00:47:26.610 --> 00:47:29.570
because of different humidity,
temperature, density,

00:47:29.570 --> 00:47:30.400
and so on.

00:47:30.400 --> 00:47:32.870
And so all these little
pockets are moving around.

00:47:32.870 --> 00:47:36.250
And that causes the star
to twinkle and to blur out.

00:47:36.250 --> 00:47:39.650
You'd like it to look like a
point, like my laser point.

00:47:39.650 --> 00:47:41.910
But if you look at it
hundreds of times a second,

00:47:41.910 --> 00:47:44.040
it looks like this thing
that, averaged over time,

00:47:44.040 --> 00:47:49.120
becomes all smeared out, smeared
into something big like this.

00:47:49.120 --> 00:47:51.010
So we'd like it
to look like that.

00:47:51.010 --> 00:47:53.700
Well, if you measure
the incoming wavefronts

00:47:53.700 --> 00:47:57.970
hundreds of times per second
with a wavefront sensor

00:47:57.970 --> 00:48:00.940
and then you send
appropriate corrections

00:48:00.940 --> 00:48:03.780
to a small,
deformable mirror, you

00:48:03.780 --> 00:48:06.280
can deform the
shape of the mirror

00:48:06.280 --> 00:48:09.620
such that when the
wave front hits it,

00:48:09.620 --> 00:48:12.590
it'll hit with exactly
the same shape.

00:48:12.590 --> 00:48:15.060
And that will then
turn a distorted wave

00:48:15.060 --> 00:48:17.342
into a plane-parallel
wave once again.

00:48:17.342 --> 00:48:18.050
You can see this.

00:48:18.050 --> 00:48:22.000
If this shape is exactly the
same as whatever wavefront

00:48:22.000 --> 00:48:24.040
is hitting it,
then what comes out

00:48:24.040 --> 00:48:26.330
will be a plane-parallel
wave again.

00:48:26.330 --> 00:48:27.050
It's fantastic.

00:48:27.050 --> 00:48:30.780
And if you do this hundreds
of times per second,

00:48:30.780 --> 00:48:34.660
then, in fact, you can
get a nice, sharp image.

00:48:34.660 --> 00:48:38.250
So your image will
be sharp not only

00:48:38.250 --> 00:48:40.380
for the star that
you've corrected,

00:48:40.380 --> 00:48:43.090
but for a small patch
of the sky next to it.

00:48:43.090 --> 00:48:45.340
So suppose you want
to study this galaxy

00:48:45.340 --> 00:48:47.874
and you've got, conveniently,
a bright star next to it.

00:48:47.874 --> 00:48:49.790
You make the measurements
of this bright star,

00:48:49.790 --> 00:48:51.831
correct it to make it look
like a point of light,

00:48:51.831 --> 00:48:54.250
like my laser pointer,
and then the correction

00:48:54.250 --> 00:48:57.390
will apply essentially
equally well to the galaxy.

00:48:57.390 --> 00:48:59.465
And that fuzzy thing
will turn into that.

00:48:59.465 --> 00:49:01.090
That's the kind of
improvement you get.

00:49:01.090 --> 00:49:03.250
Now, full disclosure--
this is actually

00:49:03.250 --> 00:49:05.610
a Hubble picture of that.

00:49:05.610 --> 00:49:07.200
And it's not that galaxy.

00:49:07.200 --> 00:49:09.547
But I couldn't find
the matching pair.

00:49:09.547 --> 00:49:11.380
I don't know that this
particular galaxy has

00:49:11.380 --> 00:49:14.230
been imaged in this way,
because, in principle, what I'm

00:49:14.230 --> 00:49:16.690
telling you is absolutely
true, even though you

00:49:16.690 --> 00:49:19.010
might be thinking, Alex just
showed us a Hubble picture

00:49:19.010 --> 00:49:20.521
and he implied
that this was taken

00:49:20.521 --> 00:49:21.770
with a ground-based telescope.

00:49:21.770 --> 00:49:24.320
So full disclosure.

00:49:24.320 --> 00:49:26.680
Well, most galaxies and
other objects in the sky

00:49:26.680 --> 00:49:29.580
don't happen to have a bright
star conveniently located next

00:49:29.580 --> 00:49:30.080
to them.

00:49:30.080 --> 00:49:31.371
Maybe this one is close enough.

00:49:31.371 --> 00:49:32.630
But all these others are not.

00:49:32.630 --> 00:49:37.580
So what we do is we create
a fake or correction

00:49:37.580 --> 00:49:41.690
star with a laser beam that
excites a layer of sodium atoms

00:49:41.690 --> 00:49:42.940
about 100 kilometers up.

00:49:42.940 --> 00:49:45.740
They're deposited there by
micrometeorites and stuff.

00:49:45.740 --> 00:49:49.780
And that whole system was
developed and perfected

00:49:49.780 --> 00:49:53.880
by Professor Claire Max, who
had an appointment at Livermore.

00:49:53.880 --> 00:49:57.990
And much of this
technology was classified

00:49:57.990 --> 00:49:59.460
until the Cold War ended.

00:49:59.460 --> 00:50:01.790
And then she started
applying it to astronomy.

00:50:01.790 --> 00:50:04.170
So this whole thing was
developed and perfected

00:50:04.170 --> 00:50:07.300
at the Lick 3-meter telescope,
moved to the Keck telescopes.

00:50:07.300 --> 00:50:10.310
And the Kecks are now the
undeniable world champions

00:50:10.310 --> 00:50:12.800
at laser guide star
adaptive optics.

00:50:12.800 --> 00:50:16.820
And why debug and
fix screws and stuff

00:50:16.820 --> 00:50:19.130
on new instruments
on telescopes where

00:50:19.130 --> 00:50:20.450
the time is really precious?

00:50:20.450 --> 00:50:23.870
Keck time is worth
$100,000 a night, OK?

00:50:23.870 --> 00:50:25.292
So you don't want
to do it there.

00:50:25.292 --> 00:50:27.750
You want to do it at a place
where it doesn't cost so much.

00:50:27.750 --> 00:50:30.180
So let me show you some results.

00:50:30.180 --> 00:50:32.760
Io, one of the moons of
Jupiter, before adaptive optics

00:50:32.760 --> 00:50:36.820
and after adaptive optics, the
most volcanically active body

00:50:36.820 --> 00:50:38.660
known in the solar system.

00:50:38.660 --> 00:50:41.610
Uranus, the seventh planet.

00:50:41.610 --> 00:50:44.420
That is the correct
pronunciation for all those

00:50:44.420 --> 00:50:46.660
above the age of seven or eight.

00:50:46.660 --> 00:50:49.120
And after adaptive optics.

00:50:49.120 --> 00:50:51.480
You can see not only the
ring, but the development

00:50:51.480 --> 00:50:54.110
of storm systems,
which could end up

00:50:54.110 --> 00:50:56.650
someday helping us to
understand Earth's atmosphere.

00:50:56.650 --> 00:50:58.480
And then one of my
favorites, the center

00:50:58.480 --> 00:51:00.120
of our galaxy in
the constellation

00:51:00.120 --> 00:51:03.180
Sagittarius before and
after adaptive optics.

00:51:03.180 --> 00:51:06.560
And this is work done by
Professor Andrea Gessa's group

00:51:06.560 --> 00:51:07.790
at UCLA.

00:51:07.790 --> 00:51:10.980
And her group and that of
Reinhard Genzel at Berkeley

00:51:10.980 --> 00:51:16.010
and Max Planck have shown that
the central stars are zipping

00:51:16.010 --> 00:51:17.840
around in Keplerian
orbits-- that

00:51:17.840 --> 00:51:21.570
means they're dominated by a
single, point-like mass-- whose

00:51:21.570 --> 00:51:23.890
location is marked
by this red cross.

00:51:23.890 --> 00:51:26.550
And the mass within there,
using Newton's laws,

00:51:26.550 --> 00:51:30.080
is 4 million solar masses
within a volume no larger

00:51:30.080 --> 00:51:31.900
than that of our solar system.

00:51:31.900 --> 00:51:34.390
And so the conservative
explanation

00:51:34.390 --> 00:51:36.760
is that this is a black hole,
a supermassive black hole.

00:51:36.760 --> 00:51:38.630
This is the single
best piece of evidence.

00:51:38.630 --> 00:51:40.230
By the way, I should
