AUDIENCE: Who knows how
many times it's happened?

01:07:07.781 --> 01:07:10.180
This universe could have
been many times before.

01:07:10.180 --> 01:07:12.250
But if, as it seems
more likely, we

01:07:12.250 --> 01:07:14.030
are in one that's
ever-expanding,

01:07:14.030 --> 01:07:16.132
does that have any
implication for, this is

01:07:16.132 --> 01:07:17.340
the first time it's happened?

01:07:17.340 --> 01:07:18.800
Or, who knows, it
could mean anything?

01:07:18.800 --> 01:07:19.770
ALEX FILIPPENKO: Yeah.

01:07:19.770 --> 01:07:21.980
Basically, I would
say still anything

01:07:21.980 --> 01:07:25.420
goes, because we don't know
what the dark energy is.

01:07:25.420 --> 01:07:28.630
The historical
precedent is that there

01:07:28.630 --> 01:07:31.860
was a dark energy-like
substance, called the inflaton,

01:07:31.860 --> 01:07:35.220
that inflated the
universe in the first 10

01:07:35.220 --> 01:07:38.140
trillionths of a trillionth of
a trillionth of a second-- 10

01:07:38.140 --> 01:07:40.260
to the minus 35 seconds.

01:07:40.260 --> 01:07:43.670
That was an accelerated,
indeed an exponential phase,

01:07:43.670 --> 01:07:45.170
of expansion of
our early universe.

01:07:45.170 --> 01:07:46.970
It's what made the universe big.

01:07:46.970 --> 01:07:51.010
But that dark energy,
that inflaton turned off.

01:07:51.010 --> 01:07:53.641
We think it decayed
from a substance

01:07:53.641 --> 01:07:55.140
with a negative
pressure-- which has

01:07:55.140 --> 01:07:57.080
this weird relativistic
effect of causing

01:07:57.080 --> 01:08:00.770
an accelerated expansion--
it decayed into normal stuff.

01:08:00.770 --> 01:08:03.450
And indeed I'm glad you asked
this question, because it gives

01:08:03.450 --> 01:08:06.330
me an excuse to tell
you that each of us--

01:08:06.330 --> 01:08:09.890
you, me, all of you--
contributed to the Big

01:08:09.890 --> 01:08:13.720
Bang itself inflation because
you consist of material

01:08:13.720 --> 01:08:15.595
that used to be the inflaton.

01:08:15.595 --> 01:08:16.470
Can you believe that?

01:08:16.470 --> 01:08:20.437
So you contributed
to the Big Bang,

01:08:20.437 --> 01:08:22.270
if the "Bang" of the
Big Bang was inflation,

01:08:22.270 --> 01:08:25.399
which I and many
people feel is probably

01:08:25.399 --> 01:08:28.620
the correct view of the early
history of the universe.

01:08:28.620 --> 01:08:32.052
So with that historical
precedent of the dark energy

01:08:32.052 --> 01:08:34.260
back then turning into stuff
that was gravitationally

01:08:34.260 --> 01:08:37.242
attractive, it's conceivable
that today's dark energy

01:08:37.242 --> 01:08:39.200
will someday become
gravitationally attractive,

01:08:39.200 --> 01:08:40.000
as well.

01:08:40.000 --> 01:08:43.100
And in that case, if there
is enough of it-- and there,

01:08:43.100 --> 01:08:46.350
we don't know which side of
the dividing line of omega

01:08:46.350 --> 01:08:49.810
equals 1 are we on--
if there's enough of it

01:08:49.810 --> 01:08:51.710
and it becomes
gravitationally attractive,

01:08:51.710 --> 01:08:54.880
then someday, the universe
will start slowing down,

01:08:54.880 --> 01:08:57.310
come to a stop,
and reverse itself.

01:08:57.310 --> 01:08:59.930
But if the total
amount of dark energy

01:08:59.930 --> 01:09:05.330
is slightly below omega
of 1, 0.9999, then

01:09:05.330 --> 01:09:08.680
even if it becomes
gravitationally attractive,

01:09:08.680 --> 01:09:11.140
the universe will continue
to expand forever.

01:09:11.140 --> 01:09:12.420
So we just don't know.

01:09:12.420 --> 01:09:16.529
And I, unfortunately, don't know
of any way we will ever know.

01:09:16.529 --> 01:09:18.229
And this is for a subtle reason.

01:09:18.229 --> 01:09:20.090
Here it is.

01:09:20.090 --> 01:09:23.170
Our observable universe
is just a small part

01:09:23.170 --> 01:09:24.310
of what we think there is.

01:09:24.310 --> 01:09:26.540
Inflation makes a
gigantic universe.

01:09:26.540 --> 01:09:30.279
And there will be fluctuations
in different observable

01:09:30.279 --> 01:09:31.779
volumes.

01:09:31.779 --> 01:09:35.560
So just like this room has an
average number of molecules

01:09:35.560 --> 01:09:37.580
per cubic centimeter,
if you take

01:09:37.580 --> 01:09:41.660
any particular cubic centimeter,
it need not be-- in fact,

01:09:41.660 --> 01:09:44.760
it usually won't be--
right at that average.

01:09:44.760 --> 01:09:47.500
It'll be a little bit above
and a little bit below.

01:09:47.500 --> 01:09:50.100
And when you're two standard
deviations away, it'll be more.

01:09:50.100 --> 01:09:50.970
But those are rare.

01:09:50.970 --> 01:09:52.090
And blah, blah, blah.

01:09:52.090 --> 01:09:56.030
If we find that the density
is very, very close to 1,

01:09:56.030 --> 01:09:59.200
then this so-called
cosmic variance

01:09:59.200 --> 01:10:03.430
tells us that what we measure
in our own observable volume

01:10:03.430 --> 01:10:05.717
need not be representative
of the whole thing,

01:10:05.717 --> 01:10:07.550
because we're so close
to the dividing line.

01:10:07.550 --> 01:10:11.600
And most observable volumes will
be close to, but not right on,

01:10:11.600 --> 01:10:12.744
the dividing line.

01:10:12.744 --> 01:10:14.160
And so they're not
representative.

01:10:14.160 --> 01:10:17.180
And so I don't
know any way around

01:10:17.180 --> 01:10:19.940
that fundamental
limitation of not

01:10:19.940 --> 01:10:24.140
being able to see outside
our observable universe.

01:10:24.140 --> 01:10:26.360
So I don't think we'll
ever know, actually.

01:10:26.360 --> 01:10:27.900
And this actually
has implications

01:10:27.900 --> 01:10:29.790
for what the geometry
of the universe is.

01:10:29.790 --> 01:10:31.645
If the omega is greater
than 1, then it's

01:10:31.645 --> 01:10:32.770
some sort of a hypersphere.

01:10:32.770 --> 01:10:34.290
It's a closed geometry.

01:10:34.290 --> 01:10:36.177
Whereas if omega
total is less than 1,

01:10:36.177 --> 01:10:38.510
then it's either flat space--
well, if it's less than 1,

01:10:38.510 --> 01:10:39.950
then it's hyperbolic geometry.

01:10:39.950 --> 01:10:42.290
If it's exactly 1, then
it's Euclidean flat space.

01:10:42.290 --> 01:10:44.020
And I don't know
that we'll ever know

01:10:44.020 --> 01:10:46.570
what the true global
geometry of the universe is.

01:10:46.570 --> 01:10:48.940
That doesn't mean we
shouldn't keep doing research

01:10:48.940 --> 01:10:50.620
at Lick Observatory
and elsewhere,

01:10:50.620 --> 01:10:51.620
and the public outreach.

01:10:51.620 --> 01:10:54.620
It just means we won't know.

01:10:54.620 --> 01:10:55.910
Yes, Dion.

01:10:55.910 --> 01:10:58.010
AUDIENCE: Alex,
how do you estimate

01:10:58.010 --> 01:11:01.805
that the dark energy is
70%, dark matter is 25%,

01:11:01.805 --> 01:11:02.680
and observable is 5%?

01:11:02.680 --> 01:11:02.820
ALEX FILIPPENKO: Yeah.

01:11:02.820 --> 01:11:04.070
So how do we get that?

01:11:04.070 --> 01:11:07.240
So how do we know that
the dark energy is 70%?

01:11:07.240 --> 01:11:10.160
There are many different
constraints, now.

01:11:10.160 --> 01:11:12.400
But let me give you the
simplest one, and the one

01:11:12.400 --> 01:11:16.160
that we originally used
in a paper back in 1998.

01:11:16.160 --> 01:11:20.150
The current acceleration
of the universe

01:11:20.150 --> 01:11:22.560
tells you who's
winning the tug of war

01:11:22.560 --> 01:11:26.210
between pushing outward--
the dark energy--

01:11:26.210 --> 01:11:29.760
and pulling inward-- normal
matter and dark matter.

01:11:29.760 --> 01:11:31.580
It's like a tug of war contest.

01:11:31.580 --> 01:11:35.170
You don't need to know the
absolute amounts of the two

01:11:35.170 --> 01:11:35.670
sides.

01:11:35.670 --> 01:11:37.294
You just need to know
their difference.

01:11:37.294 --> 01:11:39.610
Could be that one team
completely gave up

01:11:39.610 --> 01:11:42.860
and the other is pulling
with 1 unit of force.

01:11:42.860 --> 01:11:45.670
Or it could be that this
team is pulling with 1,000

01:11:45.670 --> 01:11:48.110
and the other one is
pulling with 1,001.

01:11:48.110 --> 01:11:49.080
The difference is 1.

01:11:49.080 --> 01:11:50.840
And that will have
the same effect.

01:11:50.840 --> 01:11:54.230
So the redshift
distance relationship

01:11:54.230 --> 01:11:57.870
tells us who's winning the
tug of war and by what amount.

01:11:57.870 --> 01:12:03.690
It tells us the difference
between the push and the pull,

01:12:03.690 --> 01:12:05.200
so to speak.

01:12:05.200 --> 01:12:08.770
So in a sense, omega matter
minus omega dark energy

01:12:08.770 --> 01:12:10.760
is what we get from
the supernovae.

01:12:10.760 --> 01:12:13.420
And that number is negative 0.4.

01:12:13.420 --> 01:12:15.940
Remember that number.

01:12:15.940 --> 01:12:20.000
On the other hand, the
microwave background maps,

01:12:20.000 --> 01:12:21.800
they show you these
little freckles.

01:12:21.800 --> 01:12:25.160
And from theory, it's
quite easy to calculate

01:12:25.160 --> 01:12:29.000
the spatial scale, the physical
size of a typical freckle.

01:12:29.000 --> 01:12:30.810
It turns out there's
a certain size

01:12:30.810 --> 01:12:32.450
having to do with
how far sound could

01:12:32.450 --> 01:12:34.260
have gone in the early
universe by the time

01:12:34.260 --> 01:12:35.240
these things formed.

01:12:35.240 --> 01:12:36.550
So you know the physical size.

01:12:36.550 --> 01:12:38.130
And that's relatively
independent of what

01:12:38.130 --> 01:12:39.213
the universe is doing now.

01:12:39.213 --> 01:12:40.490
It's quite model-independent.

01:12:40.490 --> 01:12:42.459
So you know the physical size.

01:12:42.459 --> 01:12:44.500
You know the angular size
because you measure it.

01:12:44.500 --> 01:12:48.030
And that then tells you
whether the light rays

01:12:48.030 --> 01:12:50.160
have been going through
a Euclidean space

01:12:50.160 --> 01:12:51.990
or not, because
you're essentially

01:12:51.990 --> 01:12:55.230
measuring whether the sum of the
interior angles of a triangle

01:12:55.230 --> 01:12:58.610
is 180 degrees, greater
than 180 degrees, or less

01:12:58.610 --> 01:13:00.680
than 180 degrees.

01:13:00.680 --> 01:13:02.876
We find that it's
equal to 180 degrees.

01:13:02.876 --> 01:13:04.750
That's what the angular
measurements show us.

01:13:04.750 --> 01:13:08.176
So it's a Euclidean space
to within the uncertainties.

01:13:08.176 --> 01:13:09.800
It could be either
way I just told you.

01:13:09.800 --> 01:13:11.990
But it's Euclidean
within the uncertainties.

01:13:11.990 --> 01:13:14.020
Well, that, according
to general relativity,

01:13:14.020 --> 01:13:16.410
tells you that the total
omega, the total density

01:13:16.410 --> 01:13:19.250
of the universe, is 1.

01:13:19.250 --> 01:13:25.360
If the difference is negative
0.4 and the sum is 1,

01:13:25.360 --> 01:13:31.430
then matter is point 0.3 and
the dark energy is point 0.7.

01:13:31.430 --> 01:13:33.550
AUDIENCE: Is that
0.4 remaining stable?

01:13:33.550 --> 01:13:34.670
ALEX FILIPPENKO: No, no.

01:13:34.670 --> 01:13:38.510
As the universe
expands, the dark energy

01:13:38.510 --> 01:13:40.980
is becoming more and more
of the dominant thing,

01:13:40.980 --> 01:13:44.740
even if its density
is not changing--

01:13:44.740 --> 01:13:46.820
if it's a property of
space, then its density

01:13:46.820 --> 01:13:49.790
doesn't change-- but
the matter gets diluted.

01:13:49.790 --> 01:13:53.110
If you have 1,000 particles
in a box and the box expands,

01:13:53.110 --> 01:13:55.400
the density of the
particles is decreasing.

01:13:55.400 --> 01:14:00.310
So as a fraction of the pie,
the matter is decreasing.

01:14:00.310 --> 01:14:03.060
And thus as a fraction of
the pie, the dark energy

01:14:03.060 --> 01:14:05.350
is increasing, even
though per unit volume,

01:14:05.350 --> 01:14:08.080
its energy density
appears to be constant.

01:14:08.080 --> 01:14:11.416
But it's always as a
fraction of the total pie.

01:14:11.416 --> 01:14:13.760
So indeed the universe
is now accelerating,

01:14:13.760 --> 01:14:15.650
but not yet exponentiating.

01:14:15.650 --> 01:14:19.610
But as the dark energy
becomes 90%, 95%, 99%,

01:14:19.610 --> 01:14:23.600
99.9% of the total,
then the acceleration

01:14:23.600 --> 01:14:28.130
will transition to
an exponentiation.

01:14:28.130 --> 01:14:31.730
The other thing, without getting
into the microwave background

01:14:31.730 --> 01:14:34.210
omega equals 1 total thing,
the other argument-- and this

01:14:34.210 --> 01:14:37.254
is one that we also use--
is that, as I told you,

01:14:37.254 --> 01:14:38.670
in the early '90s,
a lot of people

01:14:38.670 --> 01:14:42.470
were convinced that the matter
content of the universe is 0.3.

01:14:42.470 --> 01:14:46.390
So if omega M is 0.3
and omega M minus omega

01:14:46.390 --> 01:14:52.010
dark energy is negative 0.4,
then omega dark energy is 0.7.

01:14:52.010 --> 01:14:55.140
And by the way,
0.3 plus 0.7 is 1

01:14:55.140 --> 01:14:57.930
which agrees with the
microwave maps of the flatness

01:14:57.930 --> 01:14:59.880
of the universe.

01:14:59.880 --> 01:15:01.420
And now there are
several other ways

01:15:01.420 --> 01:15:02.670
of constraining that, as well.

01:15:02.670 --> 01:15:05.120
So the so-called
concordance cosmology

01:15:05.120 --> 01:15:08.110
is now something that
is accepted by most

01:15:08.110 --> 01:15:09.650
astrophysicists that I know.

01:15:09.650 --> 01:15:12.099
We're still completely
befuddled by this.

01:15:12.099 --> 01:15:13.640
It's not your
grandmother's universe.

01:15:13.640 --> 01:15:15.740
It's not what we asked for.

01:15:15.740 --> 01:15:19.150
But it appears to be that
that's what our universe is.

01:15:19.150 --> 01:15:22.320
Or-- and Noelle will confirm
that sometimes I wake up

01:15:22.320 --> 01:15:26.170
screaming at night at 3:00
in the morning-- I sometimes

01:15:26.170 --> 01:15:28.630
think that dark
matter and dark energy

01:15:28.630 --> 01:15:33.470
are our 20th and 21st
century counterparts

01:15:33.470 --> 01:15:35.690
to Ptolemaic epicycles.

01:15:35.690 --> 01:15:36.190
Right?

01:15:36.190 --> 01:15:39.590
Epicycles could
be used to explain

01:15:39.590 --> 01:15:44.140
the observed positions of
planets to arbitrary accuracy.

01:15:44.140 --> 01:15:47.490
You could add epicycles
on top of epicycles.

01:15:47.490 --> 01:15:51.980
By the way, this is a
Fourier series, right?

01:15:51.980 --> 01:15:54.140
Any periodic function
can be represented

01:15:54.140 --> 01:15:57.220
by a sum of sines of
different amplitudes, phases,

01:15:57.220 --> 01:15:58.206
and periods.

01:15:58.206 --> 01:16:00.580
Well, that's what a bunch of
circles on top of each other

01:16:00.580 --> 01:16:01.079
are.

01:16:01.079 --> 01:16:03.810
So Ptolemy invented
Fourier analysis

01:16:03.810 --> 01:16:07.560
with the first two terms
long before Fourier did,

01:16:07.560 --> 01:16:08.740
and he didn't know it.

01:16:08.740 --> 01:16:09.900
But that's what it is.

01:16:09.900 --> 01:16:13.370
It is arbitrarily accurate,
if that's all you want,

01:16:13.370 --> 01:16:17.340
is accuracy in terms of
predicted positions of planets

01:16:17.340 --> 01:16:19.800
versus observed
positions of planets.

01:16:19.800 --> 01:16:23.380
But ultimately, now-- no fault
of Ptolemy's-- we know that

01:16:23.380 --> 01:16:24.600
it's wrong.

01:16:24.600 --> 01:16:28.090
He was brilliant for having
conceived of the idea.

01:16:28.090 --> 01:16:29.660
And it lasted 1,500 years.

01:16:29.660 --> 01:16:32.510
And he made his living
being an astrologer.

01:16:32.510 --> 01:16:35.590
And so he needed to know the
positions of Mars and stuff.

01:16:35.590 --> 01:16:37.020
And it worked well.

01:16:37.020 --> 01:16:39.380
But it ended up being wrong.

01:16:39.380 --> 01:16:41.510
So dark matter and
dark energy are simply

01:16:41.510 --> 01:16:46.280
our best current descriptions
to try to explain what we see.

01:16:46.280 --> 01:16:48.200
But they may well be wrong.

01:16:48.200 --> 01:16:51.540
And what I'm hoping is that
one of the youngsters excited

01:16:51.540 --> 01:16:54.040
by Google Making Science
and Lick Observatory

01:16:54.040 --> 01:17:01.010
will figure out what it
is if it is indeed wrong.

01:17:01.010 --> 01:17:02.120
AUDIENCE: Thank you, Alex.

01:17:02.120 --> 01:17:02.950
We really appreciate it.

01:17:02.950 --> 01:17:03.250
ALEX FILIPPENKO: Thank you.

01:17:03.250 --> 01:17:04.150
Thank you.

01:17:04.150 --> 01:17:07.500
[APPLAUSE]

